ted States)|Libertarian]] nominee for [[Governor of New York]]|years=[[New York gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharpe, Larry}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:2016 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:2020 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:African-American company founders]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American military personnel]]\n[[Category:African-American people in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:American gun rights activists]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:Internet people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Libertarian Party (United States)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Libertarians]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Politicians from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland Global Campus alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Sal2100", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:adding the 2020 template. since he is a vp candidate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larry_Sharpe_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "New Beacon School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                  = The New Beacon Preparatory School\n| image                 = The New Beacon Shield.jpg\n| caption               = \n| image_size            = \n| coordinates           = {{coord|51.2001|0.2765|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto                 = Dare Ex Fumo Lucem <br/>(Give light out of darkness)\n| established           = 1863\n| closed                = \n| type                  = [[Independent school (UK)|Preparatory School]]\n| religious_affiliation = \n| president             = \n| head_label            = Headmaster\n| head                  = Mike Piercy\n| r_head_label          = \n| r_head                = \n| chair_label           = \n| chair                 = \n| founder               = John Norman\n| specialist            = \n| address               = Brittains Lane\n| city                  = Sevenoaks\n| county                = Kent\n| country               = England\n| postcode              = TN13 2PB\n| local_authority       = \n| ofsted                = \n| staff                 = \n| enrolment             = c. 360\n| gender                = Boys\n| lower_age             = 4\n| upper_age             = 13\n| publication           = \n| free_label_1          = \n| free_1                = \n| free_label_2          = \n| free_2                = \n| free_label_3          = \n| free_3                = \n| colours               = Red and navy\n{{color box|Red}} {{color box|Navy}}\n| website               = {{url|www.newbeacon.org.uk}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Beacon Preparatory School''' is an independent all-boys [[Preparatory school (UK)|preparatory school]], located at [[Sevenoaks]] in the [[English county]] of [[Kent]]. It admits both day students and [[boarding school|boarders]] aged between 4 and 13. The school also now offers a co-educational nursery for children 3 years of age and over. The school was founded in 1863, and has been on the current site since 1900. It had 62 students in 1913, and had grown to 400 students by 2008.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/School-History |title=School History |publisher=New Beacon School |accessdate=2015-08-31}} (The school's History webpage suggests Constantine was headmaster from 1976 and served 32 years, so when \"numbers grew to reach four hundred with excellence at Common Entrance and Scholarship examinations being maintained\" that would be 2008.)</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the spring term 1882, J. S. Norman along with his good friend Frank Ritchie took over '''The Beacon''', which had been established as a Preparatory school in 1863 at 18 St John's Road, Sevenoaks. As the numbers in the school grew, larger premises were needed leading to the decision in October 1897 to build a new boarding school in Sevenoaks. Land was acquired from [[William Amherst, 3rd Earl Amherst|Lord Amherst]]'s [[Montreal Park]] estate at Cross Keys, and construction of '''The New Beacon''' began in February 1899. The new building was ready by the end of the Autumn Term 1899.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1900 the New Beacon opened for the (continued) education of boys in a building with a capacity for 60 boarders. The exterior of the building changed little over the century, but the addition of a chapel in 1912 meant that the children no longer had to walk to [[Kippington]]. By 1913 the school had grown to 62 pupils and the fees were \u00a3120 per year for boarding and tuition, plus \u00a31 11s 6d for medical attendance. Other facilities included swimming baths, a miniature rifle range, a playground and two sports fields. During the First World War, staffing was depleted and the school's grounds and gardens had to be tended by staff and pupils. Thirty-seven former pupils were killed during the war, and another 75 Beaconians fell in the Second World War. Their names are noted on a memorial in the chapel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newbeacon.org.uk/about-us/history/|title=History|website=New Beacon School|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war changes and the increase in day boys===\nAfter the war numbers continued to grow and the roll call was over 120 pupils in 1948. Over the next few decades, the school tripled in size. The appointment of Rowland Constantine in 1976 saw the end of a long run of headmasters from the Norman family; Constantine was in post for 32 years.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518 |author-link= }}\n</ref>\n\nThe New Beacon is now predominantly a day school. In 2008 Mike Piercy was appointed as Headmaster and is the current incumbent.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Notable former pupils==\nWriters\n*[[Siegfried Sassoon]], First World War poet<ref>[http://www.courier.co.uk/Kent-8217-s-greatest-WW1-poet-goes-online/story-22069162-detail/story.html \"First World War journals of Tunbridge Wells poet Siegfried Sassoon go online\", ''Kent & Sussex Courier'', 4 August 2014]. Accessed 16 Feb 2015</ref>\n*[[Anthony Powell]], novelist\n*[[Henry Green]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Prep School Children: A Class Apart |first=Vyvyen |last=Brendon |date=2009 |location=Great Britain |publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=1847062873 |author-link= }}</ref> Novelist\nMilitary\n*[[Air Vice Marshall]] [[Cresswell Clementi]], CB, CBE.\n*[[Brigadier]] [[Archer Clive]], was a British Army officer who served during World War II.\n*[[Vice Admiral]] [[Timothy Laurence|Sir Timothy Laurence]], second husband of [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\nPolitics\n*[[Sherard Cowper-Coles|Sir Sherard Cowper-Coles]], diplomat\n*[[Charles Thomas Mills]], Conservative politician and [[Baby of the House]], killed in action in First World War\n*[[Arthur Mills, 3rd Baron Hillingdon]], Conservative politician\n*[[Lord Mayhew of Twysden]], former political advisor for Northern Ireland\nSport\n*[[Douglas Carr]], Cricketer, named one of Wisden's five Cricketers of the year in 1910. One England Cap.\n*[[Eliot Druce]], Cricketer\n*[[Sam Billings]], Kent and England cricketer\n*[[Joseph Choong]], tri-athlete\n*[[Ben Earl]], Saracens and England rugby player\n*[[Zak Crawley]], Kent and England cricketer\nOther\n*[[Charles Ede]], founder of the [[Folio Society]]\n*[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]], landowner, creator of [[Longleat]] safari park\n*John Alexander Thynne, Viscount Weymouth, eldest son of 5th Marquess of Bath, killed near Vermelles on the 16th February 1916.<ref>[http://www.wiltshireatwar.org.uk/story/longleats-fallen-heir-john-alexander-thynne/ \"Longleat's Fallen heir\"]</ref>\n\n==Headmasters==\n'''The Beacon''' \n*John Stewart Norman and Frank Ritchie, Joint Headmasters 1882\u20131900\n'''The New Beacon'''\n*John Stewart Norman 1900-1929\n*Frank Norman and Cecil Norman, Joint Headmasters 1929\u20131945\n*Cecil Norman 1945\u20131964\n*Denis Pratten 1964\n*John Norman 1964\u20131976\n*Rowland Constantine 1976\u20132008\n*Michael Piercy 2008\u2013present<ref>The New Beacon {{ISBN|0356219518}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2014, the Charity Commission for England and Wales urged New Beacon School to apologise to a former pupil in respect of statements made by the school to the Press.<ref name=\"urges-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Charity body urges The New Beacon School to reconsider apology over \"predatory paedophile\" |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=24 October 2014|author=Doug Kempster }}</ref> The statements related to allegations made by the boy against Paul Woodward, a former music teacher, for abusing him at the school between 2005 and 2006.<ref name=\"jailed-ver1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/3447897/Music-teacher-at-prep-school-jailed-for-sexual-abuse-of-boys.html |title=Music teacher at prep school jailed for sexual abuse of boys |date=12 Nov 2008 |publisher=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) made an award to the boy in compensation for the abuse the CICA found he had suffered. The ''Sevenoaks Chronicle'' reported that Woodward, who was convicted of sexual misconduct offences against other children and sent to prison indefinitely had been suspended from his post at the school during a previous police investigation involving allegations of sexual abuse but had been allowed back to work by a previous headmaster.<ref name=\"suspended-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Teacher was suspended then allowed back to work |publisher=[[Kent and Sussex Courier]] |date= November 13, 2008}}</ref> The school apologised to the child in 2015, and applauded him for his bravery in bringing Woodward to justice. The victim said that the apology came \"too late\".<ref name=\"toolate-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Sevenoaks school apology for sexual abuse 'too late' for teacher's victim |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=April 30, 2015 |author=Doug Kempster}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Beacon Preparatory School}}\n[[Category:Schools in Sevenoaks]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                  = The New Beacon Preparatory School\n| image                 = The New Beacon Shield.jpg\n| caption               = \n| image_size            = \n| coordinates           = {{coord|51.2001|0.2765|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto                 = Dare Ex Fumo Lucem <br/>(Give light out of darkness)\n| established           = 1863\n| closed                = \n| type                  = [[Independent school (UK)|Preparatory School]]\n| religious_affiliation = \n| president             = \n| head_label            = Headmaster\n| head                  = Mike Piercy\n| r_head_label          = \n| r_head                = \n| chair_label           = \n| chair                 = \n| founder               = John Norman\n| specialist            = \n| address               = Brittains Lane\n| city                  = Sevenoaks\n| county                = Kent\n| country               = England\n| postcode              = TN13 2PB\n| local_authority       = \n| ofsted                = \n| staff                 = \n| enrolment             = c. 360\n| gender                = Boys\n| lower_age             = 4\n| upper_age             = 13\n| publication           = \n| free_label_1          = \n| free_1                = \n| free_label_2          = \n| free_2                = \n| free_label_3          = \n| free_3                = \n| colours               = Red and navy\n{{color box|Red}} {{color box|Navy}}\n| website               = {{url|www.newbeacon.org.uk}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Beacon Preparatory School''' is an independent all-boys [[Preparatory school (UK)|preparatory school]], located at [[Sevenoaks]] in the [[English county]] of [[Kent]]. It admits both day students and [[boarding school|boarders]] aged between 4 and 13. The school also now offers a co-educational nursery for children 3 years of age and over. The school was founded in 1863, and has been on the current site since 1900. It had 62 students in 1913, and had grown to 400 students by 2008.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/School-History |title=School History |publisher=New Beacon School |accessdate=2015-08-31}} (The school's History webpage suggests Constantine was headmaster from 1976 and served 32 years, so when \"numbers grew to reach four hundred with excellence at Common Entrance and Scholarship examinations being maintained\" that would be 2008.)</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the spring term 1882, J. S. Norman along with his good friend Frank Ritchie took over '''The Beacon''', which had been established as a Preparatory school in 1863 at 18 St John's Road, Sevenoaks. As the numbers in the school grew, larger premises were needed leading to the decision in October 1897 to build a new boarding school in Sevenoaks. Land was acquired from [[William Amherst, 3rd Earl Amherst|Lord Amherst]]'s [[Montreal Park]] estate at Cross Keys, and construction of '''The New Beacon''' began in February 1899. The new building was ready by the end of the Autumn Term 1899.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1900 the New Beacon opened for the (continued) education of boys in a building with a capacity for 60 boarders. The exterior of the building changed little over the century, but the addition of a chapel in 1912 meant that the children no longer had to walk to [[Kippington]]. By 1913 the school had grown to 62 pupils and the fees were \u00a3120 per year for boarding and tuition, plus \u00a31 11s 6d for medical attendance. Other facilities included swimming baths, a miniature rifle range, a playground and two sports fields. During the First World War, staffing was depleted and the school's grounds and gardens had to be tended by staff and pupils. Thirty-seven former pupils were killed during the war, and another 75 Beaconians fell in the Second World War. Their names are noted on a memorial in the chapel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newbeacon.org.uk/about-us/history/|title=History|website=New Beacon School|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-war changes and the increase in day boys===\nAfter the war numbers continued to grow and the roll call was over 120 pupils in 1948. Over the next few decades, the school tripled in size. The appointment of Rowland Constantine in 1976 saw the end of a long run of headmasters from the Norman family; Constantine was in post for 32 years.<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Beacon |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King |date=2000 |location=Great Britain |publisher=The Bath Press |isbn=0356219518 |author-link= }}\n</ref>\n\nThe New Beacon is now predominantly a day school. In 2008 Mike Piercy was appointed as Headmaster and is the current incumbent.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Notable former pupils==\nWriters\n*[[Siegfried Sassoon]], First World War poet<ref>[http://www.courier.co.uk/Kent-8217-s-greatest-WW1-poet-goes-online/story-22069162-detail/story.html \"First World War journals of Tunbridge Wells poet Siegfried Sassoon go online\", ''Kent & Sussex Courier'', 4 August 2014]. Accessed 16 Feb 2015</ref>\n*[[Anthony Powell]], novelist\n*[[Henry Green]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Prep School Children: A Class Apart |first=Vyvyen |last=Brendon |date=2009 |location=Great Britain |publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=1847062873 |author-link= }}</ref> Novelist\nMilitary\n*[[Air Vice Marshall]] [[Cresswell Clementi]], CB, CBE.\n*[[Brigadier]] [[Archer Clive]], was a British Army officer who served during World War II.\n*[[Vice Admiral]] [[Timothy Laurence|Sir Timothy Laurence]], second husband of [[Anne, Princess Royal]]\nPolitics\n*[[Sherard Cowper-Coles|Sir Sherard Cowper-Coles]], diplomat\n*[[Charles Thomas Mills]], Conservative politician and [[Baby of the House]], killed in action in First World War\n*[[Arthur Mills, 3rd Baron Hillingdon]], Conservative politician\n*[[Lord Mayhew of Twysden]], former political advisor for Northern Ireland\nSport\n*[[Douglas Carr]], Cricketer, named one of Wisden's five Cricketers of the year in 1910. One England Cap.\n*[[Eliot Druce]], Cricketer\n*[[Sam Billings]], Kent and England cricketer\n*[[Joseph Choong]], tri-athlete\n*[[Ben Earl]], Saracens and England rugby player\n*[[Zak Crawley]], Kent and England cricketer\nOther\n*[[Charles Ede]], founder of the [[Folio Society]]\n*[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]], landowner, creator of [[Longleat]] safari park\n*John Alexander Thynne, Viscount Weymouth, eldest son of 5th Marquess of Bath, killed near Vermelles on the 16th February 1916.<ref>[http://www.wiltshireatwar.org.uk/story/longleats-fallen-heir-john-alexander-thynne/ \"Longleat's Fallen heir\"]</ref>\n\n==Headmasters== \n*John Stewart Norman and Frank Ritchie, Joint Headmasters 1882\u20131900\n*John Stewart Norman 1900-1929\n*Frank Norman and Cecil Norman, Joint Headmasters 1929\u20131945\n*Cecil Norman 1945\u20131964\n*Denis Pratten 1964\n*John Norman 1964\u20131976\n*Rowland Constantine 1976\u20132008\n*Michael Piercy 2008\u2013present<ref>The New Beacon {{ISBN|0356219518}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2014, the Charity Commission for England and Wales urged New Beacon School to apologise to a former pupil in respect of statements made by the school to the Press.<ref name=\"urges-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Charity body urges The New Beacon School to reconsider apology over \"predatory paedophile\" |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=24 October 2014|author=Doug Kempster }}</ref> The statements related to allegations made by the boy against Paul Woodward, a former music teacher, for abusing him at the school between 2005 and 2006.<ref name=\"jailed-ver1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/3447897/Music-teacher-at-prep-school-jailed-for-sexual-abuse-of-boys.html |title=Music teacher at prep school jailed for sexual abuse of boys |date=12 Nov 2008 |publisher=[[The Telegraph (UK)|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) made an award to the boy in compensation for the abuse the CICA found he had suffered. The ''Sevenoaks Chronicle'' reported that Woodward, who was convicted of sexual misconduct offences against other children and sent to prison indefinitely had been suspended from his post at the school during a previous police investigation involving allegations of sexual abuse but had been allowed back to work by a previous headmaster.<ref name=\"suspended-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Teacher was suspended then allowed back to work |publisher=[[Kent and Sussex Courier]] |date= November 13, 2008}}</ref> The school apologised to the child in 2015, and applauded him for his bravery in bringing Woodward to justice. The victim said that the apology came \"too late\".<ref name=\"toolate-ver1\">{{cite news |title=Sevenoaks school apology for sexual abuse 'too late' for teacher's victim |publisher=[[Sevenoaks Chronicle]] |date=April 30, 2015 |author=Doug Kempster}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.newbeacon.org.uk/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Beacon Preparatory School}}\n[[Category:Schools in Sevenoaks]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in Kent]]\n", "name_user": "Jimvinkiss", "label": "safe", "comment": "slight adjustment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Beacon_School"}
{"title_page": "List of people from the London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe '''list of people from the [[London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham]]''' includes residents who were either born or dwelt for a substantial period within the borders of this modern [[London borough]]. It does not comprise notable individuals who only studied at educational institutions in the area.\n\n== Academia and research ==\n* [[Joseph Addison]], essayist, poet, playwright and politician; from [[Fulham]]\n* [[Cyril Aldred]], [[Egyptology|Egyptologist]], art historian, and author; born in Fulham\n* [[Arthur Blomfield]], architect. Son of [[Charles James Blomfield]] and brother of [[Lucy Elizabeth Bather]] and [[Alfred Blomfield]]; born at [[Fulham Palace]].\n* [[Valentine Britten]], [[gramophone]] librarian for the [[BBC]]; born in Fulham\n* [[Frank Broadbent]], architect born in Fulham\n* [[Tony Brooker]], computer scientist known for developing the [[Mark 1 Autocode]]; born in Fulham\n* [[William John Burchell]], explorer, naturalist, traveller, artist, and author born in Fulham\n* [[William Butts]], physician to [[Henry VIII of England]]; born in either Fulham or [[Norfolk]]\n* [[Reginald Foster Dagnall]], engineer and aircraft designer born in Fulham\n* [[Robert Dunstan]], medical doctor and political activist; lived in Fulham\n* [[Elizabeth Eger]], reader in the Department of English at [[King's College London]]\n* [[Charles James Feret]], newspaper editor and writer; lived in Fulham. Author of an exhaustive three volume history of Fulham.\n* [[Thomas Elliot Harrison]], engineer born in Fulham.\n* [[Muriel Nissel]], statistician and civil servant, born in Fulham.\n* [[Christian O'Brien]], exploration geologist and author, born in Fulham.\n* [[Melville Henry Massue]], genealogist and author, born in Fulham.\n* [[Ethel Strudwick]], headteacher and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] activist, born in Fulham.\n* [[Peter van Geersdaele]], [[conservator-restorer]], born in Fulham.\n* [[Susan Greenfield, Baroness Greenfield]], biologist and neuroscientist, born in Hammersmith.\n\n== Arts and entertainment ==\n* [[Julie Alexander]], model and actress, born in Fulham.\n* [[Alfie Allen]], actor, born in Hammersmith; brother of singer-songwriter Lily Allen.\n* [[Lily Allen]], singer-songwriter, born in Hammersmith;<ref name=mylondon>{{cite web|last= Truelove|first= Sam|title= 11 really famous people you probably didn't realise are from Hammersmith|date= 17 June 2018|website= mylondon.news|access-date= 16 March 2020|url= https://www.mylondon.news/whats-on/whats-on-news/11-really-famous-people-you-14794873.amp}}</ref> sister of actor Alfie Allen.\n* [[Bob Andrews (guitarist)|Bob Andrews]], rock guitarist, born in Fulham.\n* [[Leonard Appelbee]], painter and [[printmaker]], born in Fulham.\n* [[Bernard Archard]], actor, born in Fulham.\n* [[Neal Arden]], actor and writer, born in Fulham.\n* [[Maureen Baker (fashion designer)|Maureen Baker]], fashion designer who designed [[Wedding dress of Princess Anne|the wedding dress]] worn by [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]] for [[Wedding of Princess Anne and Mark Phillips|her wedding]] to [[Mark Phillips]]. Baker grew up in Hammersmith.\n* [[Matt Barber (actor)|Matt Barber]], actor, born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Anabel Barnston]], actress, born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Sacha Baron Cohen]], actor and comedian, born in Hammersmith.<ref name=mylondon />\n* [[Mischa Barton]], actress, born in Hammersmith.<ref name=\"hellomagazine.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/mischa-barton/ |title=Mischa Barton |work=Hello |date=24 January 1986 |accessdate=15 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708085037/http://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/mischa-barton/ |archive-date=8 July 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n* [[Lucy Elizabeth Bather]], children's writer and daughter of [[Charles James Blomfield]]; born in Fulham\n* [[Melissa Benn]], journalist and writer, born in Hammersmith; sister of politician [[Hilary Benn]].\n* [[John Berry (illustrator)|John Berry]], illustrator, born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Terry Bickers]], musician, grew up in Fulham.\n* [[John Bindon]], actor and bodyguard, born in Fulham.\n* [[Frederick Bradnum]], radio dramatist, producer, and director born in Fulham.\n* [[Paul Brett]], [[classic rock]] guitarist, born in Fulham.\n* [[Christina Broom]], Scottish photographer credited as \"the UK's first female [[press photographer]]\"; lived on Munster Road in Fulham.\n* [[Irene Mary Browne]], sculptor and potter, born in Fulham\n* [[Florence Brudenell-Bruce]], model and former [[Bollywood]] actress, grew up in Fulham.\n* [[Kenneth Budd]], [[mural]] artist, born in Fulham.\n* [[Edward Burne-Jones]], artist and designer associated with the phase of the [[Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood|Pre-Raphaelite movement]]. Lived in [[North End, Fulham]].\n* [[Georgiana Burne-Jones]], artist and biographer of her husband, Edward Burne-Jones. One of the [[MacDonald sisters]] and mother of artist [[Philip Burne-Jones]]. Lived in North End, Fulham.\n* [[Scarlett Byrne]], actress, born in Hammersmith. She is known for portraying [[Pansy Parkinson]] in the ''[[Harry Potter]]'' [[Harry Potter (film series)|films]].\n* [[Bruce Byron]], actor, born in Fulham.\n* [[Richard Campbell (classical musician)|Richard Campbell]], classical musician, born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Lisa Coleman (actress)|Lisa Coleman]], actress, born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Fay Compton]], actress, born in Fulham; sister of actress Viola Compton.\n* [[Viola Compton]], actress, born in Fulham; sister of actress Fay Compton.\n* [[Michael Cook (playwright)|Michael Cook]], Canadian playwright, born in Fulham.\n* [[Jill Craigie]], one of Britain's earliest women's documentary makers;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jillcraigiefilmpioneer.org/jill-craigie/|title=JILL CRAIGIE 1911\u20131999|website=Jill Craigie|access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref> born in Fulham.\n* [[Elizabeth Craven]], author and playwright. Daughter of [[Augustus Berkeley, 4th Earl of Berkeley]], and second wife of [[Alexander, Margrave of Brandenburg-Ansbach|Charles Alexander, Margrave of Brandenburg-Ansbach]], with whom she lived on their properties in Fulham and Hammersmith.\n* [[Ross Cullum]], composer, record producer, songwriter, born in Fulham.\n* [[Benedict Cumberbatch]], actor, born in Hammersmith.<ref name=mylondon />\n* [[James D'Arcy]], actor, raised in Fulham.\n* [[Jill Dando]], journalist, television presenter, and newsreader, lived in Fulham.\n* [[Ben de Pear]], editor for [[Channel 4 News]], born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Cara Delevingne]], model, actress, and singer, born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Lily Donaldson]], model.\n* [[Benjamin Rawlinson Faulkner]], portrait-painter; lived in Fulham.\n* [[Meriel Forbes]], actress, born in Fulham.\n* [[John Ford (musician)|John Ford]], singer-songwriter, and musician, born in Fulham.\n* [[Example (musician)|Elliot John Gleave]], musician, singer, rapper, and songwriter, better known by his stage name, Example; born in Hammersmith.\n* [[Emilia Fox]], actress, born in Hammersmith;<ref name=dob>{{cite web|title=Emilia Fox: A long line of theatrical ancestors...|url=http://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/featuredarticles/2011/who-do-you-think-you-are/emilia-fox-65/|publisher=The Genealogist|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> sister of actor Freddie Fox.<ref name=mirroremilia>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/latest/2010/05/14/emilia-s-pouting-tips-for-freddie-115875-22258137/ |title=Emilia's pouting tips for Freddie |work=Daily Mirror |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=11 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202110624/http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/latest/2010/05/14/emilia-s-pouting-tips-for-freddie-115875-22258137/ |archivedate=2 February 2011 }}</ref>\n* [[Freddie Fox (actor)|Freddie Fox]], actor, born in Hammersmith; brother of actress E