ory|Arecibo Observatory}}\n* {{Official website|www.naic.edu}}\n* [http://www.naic.edu/~pradar/pradar.htm Arecibo Planetary Radar]\n* [http://areciboscience.org Arecibo Science Advocacy Partnership]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131104160330/http://www.naic.edu/general/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=192&Itemid=638 \u00c1ngel Ramos Foundation Visitor Center]\n* [http://setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu SETI@home ]\n* [http://www.ieeeghn.org/wiki/index.php/Milestones:NAIC/Arecibo_Radiotelescope,_1963 IEEE History Center \u2013 IEEE Milestones: NAIC/Arecibo Radiotelescope]\n* [http://www.lofar.nl Lofar]\n* [https://archive.today/20121209021309/http://arecibo-observatory.org/ The Arecibo Observatory Contributions Site]\n* [http://setiathome.berkeley.edu/arecibo_letter.php Letter to save Arecibo Observatory]\n\n{{Radio-astronomy|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n{{Extraterrestrial life}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1963]]\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Historic Mechanical Engineering Landmarks]]\n[[Category:National Science Foundation]]\n[[Category:Radio telescopes]]\n[[Category:Search for extraterrestrial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Science museums in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:University museums in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Museums in Arecibo, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in Puerto Rico]]\n", "name_user": "105.225.155.163", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arecibo_Observatory"}
{"title_page": "James John Joicey", "text_new": "{{short description|English amateur entomologist (1870\u20131932)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = James John Joicey\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] [[Zoological Society of London|FZS]] [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] [[Royal Horticultural Society|FRHS]]\n| image              = BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumJoicey cropped.jpg\n| alt                = Sepia portrait photograph of middle-aged gentleman in suit and hat in 1920\n| birth_date         = 28 December 1870\n| birth_place        = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n| death_date         = 10 March 1932\n| death_place        = The Hill, [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], England\n| burial_place       = Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]]\n| occupation         = Amateur [[entomologist]]\n| known_for          = Assembling a collection of over 1.5&nbsp;million [[Lepidoptera]] specimens, his Hill Museum research output, and his presentations from his collection to the [[Natural History Museum]]\n| notable_works      = ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin2\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin3\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin4\"/>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Maud Muriel Fisher|1896}}\n| relatives          = [[James Joicey, 1st Baron Joicey|1st Baron Joicey]] (father's cousin)<ref name=\"Major\"/>\n}}\n\n'''James John Joicey''' [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] (28 December 1870 \u2013 10 March 1932) was an English amateur [[entomologist]], who assembled an extensive collection of [[Lepidoptera]] in his private research museum, called the Hill Museum, in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]]. His collection, 40 years in the making, was considered to have been the second largest in the world held privately and to have numbered over 1.5 million [[Biological specimen|specimens]]. Joicey was a [[fellow]] of the [[Zoological Society of London]], the [[Royal Geographical Society]], the [[Royal Entomological Society]], the [[Royal Horticultural Society]], and the [[Linnean Society of London]].\n\nJoicey employed specialist entomologists including [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]] to curate his collection and financed numerous expeditions throughout the world to obtain previously unknown varieties. More than 190 scientific articles were produced during the active period of the Hill Museum. This body of research was described as \"a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value\".<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n\nJoicey's donations from his collection, made both during his life and following his death, contributed significantly to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London. Joicey's obituary in ''[[Royal Entomological Society|The Entomologist]]'' described him as \"undoubtedly the most lavish patron of Entomology, in so far as butterflies and moths are concerned, that this country has ever boasted\".<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|142}}\n\n==Life==\n===Background===\nJames John Joicey was born on 28 December 1870 in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], the only child of Major William James Joicey, a wealthy coal owner, and Mary Anne Joicey n\u00e9e Clark.<ref name=\"Major\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Births|last=|first=|date=6 January 1871|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 March 1868|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref> He was educated at [[Aysgarth School]], [[Yorkshire]], and [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]], [[Oxford]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey Owner of \u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer|access-date=|page=14}}</ref> and was an Associate Member of the [[Institution of Mining Engineers|Institute of Mining Engineers]] from 1891.<ref name=\"IME\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=List of Members, August 3, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactions62nort/page/n361/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the North of England Institute of Mining and Mechanical Engineers|volume=LXII|pages=xlvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> He was also a member of the [[Junior Carlton Club]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf|title=Walford's County Families of the United Kingdom|last=|first=|publisher=Ballantyne & Co. Ltd.|year=1919|isbn=|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf/page/734 734]|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nJoicey married Maud Muriel Fisher (later Baroness de Satg\u00e9) in London in 1896.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 October 1896|work=The Standard|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He lived at The Hill in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], from about 1912.{{Refn|The 1911 Census of England shows another family living at The Hill in April 1911 and Joicey had notified the Institute of Mining Engineers of his address at The Hill by August 1912.<ref name=\"IME\"/> He is also listed in London electoral registers from 1920 to 1925 at [[Marble Arch#Marble Arch area|Marble Arch]] as Admiral Joicey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com|title=London, England, Electoral Registers, 1832\u20131965: Paddington and St Marylebone, Polling District F, No. 5, Bryanston Square Ward, 1921\u20131925|last=|first=|date=|website=ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===Collecting===\nJoicey's boyhood interest in insects was encouraged by his parents and at the age of sixteen he put together a small collection of British and foreign [[Butterfly|butterflies]].<ref name=\"Riley\">{{Cite journal|last=Riley|first=N. D.|date=1932|title=Obituary: James John Joicey|url=|journal=The Entomologist|volume=65|pages=142\u2013144|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article90080883|title=A \u00a3100,000 Hobby. The Rarest Pair of Wings in the World. Facing Death for a Butterfly|last=|first=|date=24 September 1927|work=The Adelaide Chronicle|access-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live|page=76}}</ref> As an adult, he happened upon the forgotten cabinets of his boyhood collection and was inspired to start collecting in earnest,<ref name=\":9\" /> his active interest dating from 1906.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bulletinofh112192122hill/page/n9|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1924|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=1|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> He used his resources to \"indulge a taste for collecting butterflies and [[moth]]s which remained with him throughout his life.\" He travelled \"in the East\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary \u2013 Mr. J. J. Joicey \u2013 Gifts to the Natural History Museum|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> as a young man and, although he employed experts to collect most of his specimens, also collected \"on his own account both here and abroad\"<ref name=\":9\" /> and \"travelled widely in Europe, India, China, Japan, Burma and America\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies. Death of an Eminent Naturalist|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Sheffield Independent|access-date=|page=5}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Who Was Who: 1929\u20131940|last=|first=|publisher=Adam & Charles Black|year=1960|isbn=|location=London|pages=722}}</ref> In 1913, he built and financed a private research museum, the Hill Museum, at his home in Witley, employing a [[curator]] and seven assistants.<ref name=\":1\" /> In one twelve-month period he collected some 17,000 specimens from across the world and was spending up to \u00a310,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=10000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) a year on the collection.<ref name=\":9\" /> Joicey said,\n\n<blockquote>How did I manage to spend \u00a310,000 a year on this collection? Well, these did not come from my back garden. I have had to send collectors to the far ends of the earth. ... When my work is done \u2013 that is, when I die \u2013 I will present the collection to the nation.<ref name=\":6\" />{{pb}}The work has been the ruling passion of my life, ... I don't think I am extravagant, as my researches and investigations will be of great value to the nation.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nJoicey became a fellow of the Zoological Society of London in 1890,<ref>{{Cite book|title=A List of the Fellows of the Zoological Society of London|last=|first=|publisher=William Clowes and Sons, Limited|year=1924|isbn=|location=London|pages=85}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Geographical Society in 1903,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1903|title=Meetings of the Royal Geographical Society, Sessions 1903\u20131904|url=https://archive.org/details/geographicaljou40britgoog/page/n744/mode/1up|journal=The Geographical Journal|volume=XXII|pages=709|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Entomological Society in 1908 (council member 1920\u20131923),<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1915roya/page/n23|title=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1915|last=|first=|publisher=Longmans, Green & Co.|year=1915|isbn=|location=London|pages=xix|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1912|title=Extracts from the Proceedings of the Royal Horticultural Society|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.240657/page/n779/mode/1up|journal=The Journal of the Royal Horticultural Society|volume=xxxviii|pages=xxii|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Linnean Society of London in 1913,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1914|title=December 4th, 1913|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsoflin191215linn/page/n174/mode/1up|journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society|volume=126|pages=3|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a life member of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France]] in 1921,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1931|title=Liste des membres de la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France arr\u00eat\u00e9e au 10 janvier 1930|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/bsef_0037-928x_1931_num_36_1_28972|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France|volume=36|issue=1|pages=XXVIII|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and a member of the [[London Natural History Society]] in 1928.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://archive.org/details/londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|journal=The London Naturalist|volume=1931|pages=38|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nAs well as amateur entomologist, Joicey was a well-known amateur [[Orchidaceae|orchidist]] and exhibited at meetings of the Royal Horticultural Society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey|journal=The Orchid Review|volume=40|pages=118|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\nJoicey could afford to build his collection of Lepidoptera through his family connection with the firm of \"Messrs. James Joicey & Co., Ltd, coalowners, Newcastle\", founded by his grandfather.<ref name=\"Major\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Major Joicey Dead. His Association with Local Coal Industry. Popular Turf Personality|last=|first=|date=24 January 1912|work=The Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|url-status=live|page=7}}</ref> Although described as having been \"nominally on the [[Stock exchange|Stock Exchange]] from 1896 to 1899\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Unable to Live on \u00a38,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=9 July 1910|work=Framlingham Weekly News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> then, in 1901, as a \"coal owner & ship owner\",<ref>1901 Census of England and Wales. RG12/814</ref> and, in 1913, as a director of the family coal mining firm,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=James Joicey & Co. Limited|last=|first=|date=1 December 1913|work=The Times|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> Joicey effectively had no occupation and throughout his life subsisted on substantial allowances from his parents. However, his income proved insufficient for his \"extravagance in living\" and the interest rates charged by money-lenders. Joicey became [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]] in 1909 with a deficiency of over \u00a3185,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=185000|start_year=1909|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}), and again in 1922 with a deficiency of over \u00a3430,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=430000|start_year=1922|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) despite his mother having given him \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1921|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in the interim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. In re Joicey|last=|first=|date=8 July 1910|work=The Times|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Borrowed Half a Million. Young Man's Dealings with Moneylenders|last=|first=|date=8 February 1922|work=Daily Mail|access-date=|url-status=live|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Millionaire's Son Again Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=10 February 1922|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref> The latter bankruptcy was discharged in October 1931.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey's Bankruptcy|last=|first=|date=16 October 1926|work=The Times|access-date=|page=4}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The son of a millionaire, for him money meant only one thing \u2013 more butterflies, still rarer specimens than he had already.\n| source = [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]], Joicey's head curator, 1932<ref name=\"Insects\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nJoicey's father, at one time a millionaire, had left over \u00a3700,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=700000|start_year=1912|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in his [[Estate (law)|estate]] in 1912, but his will ensured that no money went directly to his son.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Man Unable to Live on \u00a320,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Will of the Late Major W. J. Joicey|last=|first=|date=27 March 1912|work=Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|page=2}}</ref> The Witley house and estate were bought for Joicey after his first bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Wild Extravagance. Debts of \u00a3400,000 in Second Bankruptcy. Remarkable Figures|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Times|access-date=|page=12}}</ref> When sued by [[creditor]]<nowiki/>s in 1919, the judge said, \"He seems hardly to have grown up. He seems to have infantile tastes which his mother helps him gratify.\" When [[counsel]] stated that Joicey was \"susceptible to the wiles of the money-lenders\", the judge responded, \"And to the wiles of the butterflies.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. A Butterfly Collector and Moneylenders. Jacobs Brothers v. Joicey|last=|first=|date=31 March 1919|work=The Times|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> During the 1922 bankruptcy hearing, Joicey said, \"I think the money seems to have gone like snow in an oven.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Money Went Like Snow in Oven|last=|first=|date=7 March 1922|work=Pall Mall Gazette|access-date=|page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nJoicey's mother died in 1930, leaving an estate valued at over \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1930|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=Mary|date=1930|website=gov.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of his life, Joicey became an \"invalid\".<ref name=\"Insects\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a310,000 A Year for Butterflies \u2013 Insects Men Died to Get \u2013 Wonder Collection for Nation|last=|first=|date=15 March 1932|work=Dundee Evening Telegraph|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> He died of heart failure on 10 March 1932 at his home, The Hill, in Witley, Surrey, aged 61.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=21 March 1932|title=Milestones|url=|journal=Time Magazine|volume=XIX|issue=12|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Deaths|last=|first=|date=14 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He was buried at Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Arrangements for Today|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Joicey's estate was valued at \u00a31,151 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=1151|start_year=1932|r=-2|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=James John|date=1932|website=gov.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> his collection and museum having been principally paid for and owned by his mother.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Museum Bequest of Northern Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=7 June 1932|work=Sunderland Daily Echo and Shipping Gazette|access-date=|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Hambledon and Witley Estates|last=|first=|date=28 May 1932|work=The Surrey Advertiser and County Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The primary object of Mr. Joicey in making this collection of Lepidoptera is to advance in some way our scientific knowledge. ... The formation of a large collection has its value, because without access to plenty of material studies can only be incomplete and results are often erroneous. ... <br/>\nNo apology should be needed for amassing large collections ...\n| source = George Talbot, 1924<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|5}}\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nAs an adult, Joicey began collecting Lepidoptera in 1906{{Refn|According to Miller,<ref name=\"Miller\" /> Joicey first competed with [[Walter Rothschild]] to build the world's premier orchid collection but when Joicey went bankrupt the judge made him promise to abandon collecting orchids. However, the details of the anecdote do not match Joicey's known bankruptcies and the story is currently uncorroborated.|group=lower-alpha}} and by 1908 was advertising as far away as Australia for:\n\n<blockquote>Fresh-caught Specimens of Butterflies and Large Moths, in papers. Send Samples and state price per hundred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/163231414?searchTerm=%22james%20joicey%22|title=Wanted|last=|first=|date=30 December 1908|work=The Sydney Mail and New South Wales Advertiser|access-date=6 December 2019|page=1683}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe acquired the [[Henley Grose-Smith]] collection in 1910. Two years later he purchased the [[Herbert Druce]] collection. To house his growing collection, he founded the Hill Museum at his [[Witley]] home in 1913.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3}}<ref name=\":1\" /> Joicey employed curators, including [[Alfred Noakes]] (from 1906)<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Lance\u2013Corpl. Noakes Killed|last=|first=|date=20 November 1916|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=Proceedings of the Entomological Society of London for 1912: Wednesday, October 16th, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1912roya/page/n1141/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London|volume=1912|pages=xcvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and George Talbot (from 1915),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1954|title=President's Address. 28th January 1953|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingstrans19501953sout/page/62|journal=Proceedings and Transactions of the South London Entomological and Natural History Society|volume=1952\u201353|pages=62|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> with a staff of assistants.<ref name=\"Riley\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Society|last=|first=|date=8 August 1914|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BulletinHillMuseumPlate9.jpg|thumb|338x338px|New butterflies from [[Buru]] and [[New Guinea]]<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|592}} (Joicey Collection). Top left: [[Troides prattorum]]. Top right: [[Charaxes mars|Charaxes madensis]]. Both were described by Talbot at The Hill to a reporter in 1932 shortly after Joicey's death.<ref name=\"Insects\" />|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|left]]\n\nBetween 1913 and 1921 Joicey bought further collections: those of [[Ernst Suffert]], {{Circa|1913}}, [[Fritz Ludwig Otto Wichgraf]], 1913, [[Charles Swinhoe|Col. Charles Swinhoe]], 1916, [[Roland Trimen]], 1917, [[Charles George Nurse|Lt.-Col. C. G. Nurse]], 1919, [[Hamilton Herbert Druce|Hamilton Druce]], 1919, [[Heinrich Riffarth]], 1919, [[Henry John Elwes]], 1920, and [[Paul Dognin]], 1921. He added to these by sending special collectors to explore various regions on his behalf; for example, the [[Antwerp Edgar Pratt|Pratt family]] to [[South America]] and [[New Guinea]], and [[T. A. Barns]] to [[Central Africa]] (Barns dedicated his [[iarchive:wonderlandofeast00barnrich/page/n7|1922 book]] on the Eastern [[Belgian Congo|Congo]] to Joicey, his \"friend and patron\"). Mr. W. J. C. Frost, who visited the Islands of [[Tanimbar Islands|Tenimber]], Am, Key, [[Misool|Misol]], Obi and Sula during 1915\u20131918, donated his collection. Another collector, Mr. C. Talbot Bowring,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Weddings Today. Mr C. T. Bowring and Miss Parker|last=|first=|date=29 October 1908|work=The Globe|access-date=|page=8}}</ref> sent many thousands of specimens from Hainan Island (1918\u20131920).<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3\u20134}}\n\nIn 1916, when granting Joicey's curator conditional exemption from military service, [[Josceline Wodehouse|General Sir J. Wodehouse]] described the collection as \"probably the finest of its kind in England\", and Oxford professor [[Edward Bagnall Poulton|E. B. Poulton]] wrote that \"to leave the collection without a competent head would be a national disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Expensive Butterflies|last=|first=|date=31 August 1916|work=Illustrated Police News|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> \n\nIn 1919, the collection was valued at \u00a350,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=50000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}). It consisted of 1.5&nbsp;million specimens held in a room containing chests of drawers with \"5000 compartments neatly arranged round the room, and in addition 4000&nbsp;cases, all carefully labelled.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/star/1919/06/06/4|title=A Fortune for Butterflies. A Collector's Mania. Spends \u00a310,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=6 June 1919|work=The Star|access-date=20 November 2019|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> It was reported that,\n\n<blockquote>Here were butterflies of all sizes, of all colours \u2013 all arranged in an effective colour grouping. In one compartment were ... great winged beauties half a foot from wing tip to wing tip. In another were creatures so small that it needed a microscope to discern their beauty.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>\n\nAn annexe to the museum \"over eighty feet long by twenty feet wide\" (approximately 24 by 6&nbsp;m) was built in 1920.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|4}} In 1927 it was reported that the main building of the Museum was \"as large as a dance hall. The specimens are kept in special cabinets stacked almost to the roof. Here, all day long, Mr. Joicey and his assistants ... work at arranging and naming the fresh arrivals.\" Some specimens dated from the 1830s, others were obtained on the [[Henry Morton Stanley|Stanley]] expedition of 1871. Some were caught over 1,000&nbsp;miles (1,600&nbsp;km) from land, others had perished on the Alpine snowfields. They ranged in size from 1/2&nbsp;inch to 10&nbsp;inches (approximately 1&nbsp;cm to 25&nbsp;cm) wing spread.<ref name=\":9\" /> By 1930 the Hill Museum contained upwards of 380,000 specimens.<ref name=\"Riley\" />\n\n[[File:JJ Joicey butterfly cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum.jpg|thumb|Butterflies from the Joicey collection in a contemporary cabinet at the [http://www.haslemeremuseum.co.uk/ Haslemere Educational Museum].|alt=Photograph of multi-drawer butterfly display cabinet with some drawers open]]\n\nJoicey and his Hill Museum colleagues published more than 190 scientific articles on world Lepidoptera and \"produced some excellent work, especially on the Lepidoptera of New Guinea, [[Hainan]] Island, and Central and [[East Africa|Eastern Africa]].\"<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=Lee D.|date=1986|title=Presidential Address, 1984: A Tribute to the Amateur|url=http://images.peabody.yale.edu/lepsoc/jls/1980s/1986/1986-40(1)1-Miller.pdf|journal=Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society|volume=40|issue=1|pages=1\u20137|access-date=20 November 2019|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|4}} Joicey and Talbot co-edited four volumes of ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'', 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" /><ref name=\"Bulletin2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1928|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=2|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin3\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1929|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=3|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin4\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1932|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=4|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> and [[Alfred George Gabriel]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Many Local Names in New Year Honours List. Entomologist|last=|first=|date=9 January 1958|work=Harrow Observer|access-date=|url-status=live|page=9}}</ref> published ''A Catalogue of the Type Specimens of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum'' in 1932.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDuring his lifetime, Joicey \"presented to the Nation\" between 200,000 and 300,000 Lepidoptera specimens including about 75,000 to the Natural History Museum. The latter figure included 15,500 moths and a number butterflies (1923), his whole collection of over 30,000 [[Skipper (butterfly)|Hesperiidae]] butterflies (1926), 6,000 [[Lymantriinae|Lymantriidae]] moths (1928), and, in 1931, a series of 800 [[Type (biology)|type]] butterflies being \"the most valuable, both scientifically and intrinsically ... received for the past two decades\", some thousands of moths including over 600 type and [[paratype]] moths, and 1,500 butterflies including 750 type specimens. In 1932, the collection numbered over 500,000 specimens.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0|title=A Catalogue of Manuscripts in the Entomology Library of the Natural History Museum, London|last=Harvey|first=Julie M.V.|last2=Gilbert|first2=Pamela|last3=Martin|first3=Kathy|publisher=Mansell Publishing Limited|year=1996|isbn=0-7201-2290-2|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0/page/114 114]\u2013115|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Sale Room \u2013 Joicey Collection|last=|first=|date=29 April 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>\n\nHowever, shortly after Joicey's death in 1932 the Hill Museum was closed and the property sold by his mother's [[executor]]s.<ref name=\":5\" /> Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>The closing of the Hill Museum and the disbanding of its staff are events which will have serious repercussions throughout the ranks of lepidopterists in all parts of the world, and will definitely retard the advance of this science. In a comparatively short space of time Mr Joicey accomplished much for his favourite study.<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}</blockquote>\n\n<gallery caption=\"The Hill Museum\">\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumExterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of the outside of building with four arched windows|Hill Museum: Exterior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumAnnexe.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a long single-story barracks hut in a field|Hill Museum: Annexe\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumInterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a room crowded with display cabinets and work benches|Hill Museum: A part of the interior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumPhotomicrography.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of man adjusting photographic equipment on a bench|Hill Museum: Photomicrographic Department under Mr. H. J. Campbell\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1923.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of six gentlemen standing outside on pathway stairs|Joicey (second from left) and other entomologists at the Hill Museum in 1920\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Joicey Collection examples\">\nFile:BMNH(E)983480 Delias joiceyi Talb. female3 ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Delias]] joiceyi''\nFile:BMNH(E)983400 Delias maudei J.&N. male ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias maudei''\nFile:BMNH(E)141732 Delias mariae J.&T. AT female ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias mariae''\nFile:Ornithoptera goliath samson f. joiceyi Noakes & Talbot, 1915.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Ornithoptera goliath]] samson'' f. ''joiceyi''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0649.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''Ornithoptera joyceyi'' (male), two ''Delias''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0651.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of a butterfly specimen|''Ornithoptera joiceyi'' (female)\nFile:DeudorixMaudeiMFJoiceyTalbot1916.JPG|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Deudorix]] maudei''\nFile:Deudorix littoralis TypesMFUpAC1.jpg|alt=Photograph of two pinned butterflies with notes above|''Deudorix littoralis'' (male & female types)\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea and Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VIII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate IX.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New butterflies from Buru and New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate X.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New [[Sphingidae]]\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate XI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New Sphingidae\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate XII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New [[Zygaenidae]]\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0665 with explanation.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Milionia]]'', four others\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14.jpg|alt=Photograph of a drawer of pinned butterflies|South American ''[[Papilio]]''\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14 close-up.jpg|alt=Photograph of pinned butterflies with notes under each|South American ''Papilio'' (detail)    \n</gallery>\n\n==Legacy==\nJoicey's Hill Museum produced more than 190 research articles which were published in a range of scientific journals.<ref name=\"Riley\" /> In 1934, the Natural History Museum received more than 300,000 specimens as part of the Joicey Bequest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Museum: Gift of Butterfly Collection|last=|first=|date=27 March 1934|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Together with the [[Charles Oberth\u00fcr|Oberth\u00fcr]] and [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] collections, the Joicey collection contributed to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the Natural History Museum, London.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Miller\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/collections/entomology-collections/lepidoptera-collections.html|title=Lepidoptera collections|last=|first=|date=|website=National History Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=9 April 1932|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=129|issue=3258|pages=535|doi=10.1038/129535a0|access-date=22 November 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nA report in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>During his life-time, the late J. J. Joicey probably did more to stimulate the study of butterflies and moths, especially those of Africa, than any other private individual in Great Britain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=31 March 1934|title=Recent Acquisitions at the Natural History Museum|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/133490b0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=133|issue=3361|pages=490|doi=10.1038/133490b0|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Works==\n===Joicey and Talbot (partial list)===\n{{div col}}\n*New Species of Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''15''' (87): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/295|295\u2013301]], pl. [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/n662/mode/1up|XII]] (1915)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Dutch New Guinea (with A. Noakes). ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''63''' (3,4): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/361/mode/1up|361\u2013386]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/n587|LV\u2013LXII]] (1916)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Schouten Islands. ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''64''' (1): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/65/mode/1up|65\u201383]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/n151|3\u20136]] (1916)\n*New Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (115): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/50|50\u201387]], pls [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/n484/mode/1up|1\u20134]] (1917)\n*New Lepidoptera from Waigeu, Dutch New Guinea and Biak. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (117): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/216|216\u2013229]] (1917)\n*New South-American Rhopalocera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/259/mode/1up|259\u2013264]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New South-American Arctiidae. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/265/mode/1up|265\u2013270]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New butterflies from Africa and the east. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/271/mode/1up|271\u2013272]] (1918)\n*A Gynandromorph of ''Papilio lycophron'' Hbn. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/273/mode/1up|273]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n379/mode/1up|II]] (1918)\n*Three Aberrations of Lepidoptera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/275/mode/1up|275\u2013276]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New forms of Indo-Australian butterflies. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''1''' (3): [https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/565/mode/1up 565\u2013569] (1924)\n*New forms of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. ''Encyclopedia of Entomology'' (B III Lepidoptera) '''2''': 1\u201314 (1926)\n*New forms of Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''2''' (1): [[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n29|19\u201327]] (1928)\n*Also see the [http://bionames.org/authors/J%20J%20Joicey BioNames database] linking taxonomic names to their original descriptions\n{{div col end}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The majority of the papers are of a purely [[Systematics|systematic]] nature, consisting of the description of new [[species]] or the revision of various [[Genus|genera]]; but there are several of principally [[Fauna|faunistic]] interest, as, for example, the Catalogue of the Lepidoptera of Hainan. They represent a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value.\n| source = Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'', 1932<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\n===Associated with the Hill Museum===\n'''''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum''''' (111 articles and 80 plates<ref name=\"Riley\" />)\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n12/mode/1up 1921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n13/mode/2up 1921\u20131924]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n15/mode/2up 1924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n7/mode/2up|1928]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n7/mode/2up|1929]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n7/mode/1up|1931]]\n\n'''''Other journals''''' (82 articles<ref name=\"Riley\" />) (partial list)\n\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/13/mode/1up 1914\u20131916]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/14/mode/2up 1916\u20131921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/572/mode/1up 1921\u20131924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n207/mode/2up|1924\u20131927]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Summaries==\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomological News'' '''43''': [[iarchive:entomologicalnew42amer/page/140/mode/1up|140]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''London Naturalist'' '''1931''': [[iarchive:londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|38]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Nature'' '''129''': [https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf 535], [https://www.nature.com/articles/129896a0.pdf 896]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.]  ''Orchid Review'' '''40''': [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey 118]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.] ''The Times'' (16 March) p.&nbsp;9\n*Gilbert, P.  2000: ''Butterfly Collectors and Painters: Four Centuries of Colour Plates from the Library Collections of the Natural History Museum, London''. Singapore, Beaumont Publishing Pte Ltd: X+166 S, pp. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WQBNAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Butterfly+Collectors+and+Painters.+Four+centuries+of+colour+plates+from+The+Library+Collections+of+The+Natural+History+Museum%2C+London.%22&q=joicey 31]\u201333\n*Riley, N. D. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist'' '''65''': 142\u2013144\n*Turner, H. J. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist's Record & Journal of Variation'' '''44''': [[iarchive:entomologistsr441932tutt/page/68/mode/1up|68]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=James John Joicey}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/205188852/james-john-joicey Grave site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joicey, James John}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:British entomologists]]\n[[Category:English lepidopterists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Entomological Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Zoological Society of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English amateur entomologist (1870\u20131932)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = James John Joicey\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] [[Zoological Society of London|FZS]] [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] [[Royal Horticultural Society|FRHS]]\n| image              = BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumJoicey cropped.jpg\n| alt                = Sepia portrait photograph of middle-aged gentleman in suit and hat in 1920\n| birth_date         = 28 December 1870\n| birth_place        = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n| death_date         = 10 March 1932\n| death_place        = The Hill, [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], England\n| burial_place       = Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]]\n| occupation         = Amateur [[entomologist]]\n| known_for          = Assembling a collection of over 1.5&nbsp;million [[Lepidoptera]] specimens, his Hill Museum research output, and his presentations from his collection to the [[Natural History Museum]]\n| notable_works      = ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin2\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin3\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin4\"/>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Maud Muriel Fisher|1896}}\n| relatives          = [[James Joicey, 1st Baron Joicey|1st Baron Joicey]] (father's cousin)<ref name=\"Major\"/>\n}}\n\n'''James John Joicey''' [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] (28 December 1870 \u2013 10 March 1932) was an English amateur [[entomologist]], who assembled an extensive collection of [[Lepidoptera]] in his private research museum, called the Hill Museum, in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]]. His collection, 40 years in the making, was considered to have been the second largest in the world held privately and to have numbered over 1.5 million [[Biological specimen|specimens]]. Joicey was a [[fellow]] of the [[Zoological Society of London]], the [[Royal Geographical Society]], the [[Royal Entomological Society]], the [[Royal Horticultural Society]], and the [[Linnean Society of London]].\n\nJoicey employed specialist entomologists including [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]] to curate his collection and financed numerous expeditions throughout the world to obtain previously unknown varieties. More than 190 scientific articles were produced during the active period of the Hill Museum. This body of research was described as \"a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value\".<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n\nJoicey's donations from his collection, made both during his life and following his death, contributed significantly to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London. Joicey's obituary in ''[[Royal Entomological Society|The Entomologist]]'' described him as \"undoubtedly the most lavish patron of Entomology, in so far as butterflies and moths are concerned, that this country has ever boasted\".<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|142}}\n\n==Life==\n===Background===\nJames John Joicey was born on 28 December 1870 in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], the only child of Major William James Joicey, a wealthy coal owner, and Mary Anne Joicey n\u00e9e Clark.<ref name=\"Major\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Births|last=|first=|date=6 January 1871|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 March 1868|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref> He was educated at [[Aysgarth School]], [[Yorkshire]], and [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]], [[Oxford]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey Owner of \u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer|access-date=|page=14}}</ref> and was an Associate Member of the [[Institution of Mining Engineers|Institute of Mining Engineers]] from 1891.<ref name=\"IME\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=List of Members, August 3, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactions62nort/page/n361/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the North of England Institute of Mining and Mechanical Engineers|volume=LXII|pages=xlvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> He was also a member of the [[Junior Carlton Club]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf|title=Walford's County Families of the United Kingdom|last=|first=|publisher=Ballantyne & Co. Ltd.|year=1919|isbn=|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf/page/734 734]|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nJoicey married Maud Muriel Fisher (later Baroness de Satg\u00e9) in London in 1896.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 October 1896|work=The Standard|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He lived at The Hill in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], from about 1912.{{Refn|The 1911 Census of England shows another family living at The Hill in April 1911 and Joicey had notified the Institute of Mining Engineers of his address at The Hill by August 1912.<ref name=\"IME\"/> He is also listed in London electoral registers from 1920 to 1925 at [[Marble Arch#Marble Arch area|Marble Arch]] as Admiral Joicey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com|title=London, England, Electoral Registers, 1832\u20131965: Paddington and St Marylebone, Polling District F, No. 5, Bryanston Square Ward, 1921\u20131925|last=|first=|date=|website=ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===Collecting===\nJoicey's boyhood interest in insects was encouraged by his parents and at the age of sixteen he put together a small collection of British and foreign [[Butterfly|butterflies]].<ref name=\"Riley\">{{Cite journal|last=Riley|first=N. D.|date=1932|title=Obituary: James John Joicey|url=|journal=The Entomologist|volume=65|pages=142\u2013144|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article90080883|title=A \u00a3100,000 Hobby. The Rarest Pair of Wings in the World. Facing Death for a Butterfly|last=|first=|date=24 September 1927|work=The Adelaide Chronicle|access-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live|page=76}}</ref> As an adult, he happened upon the forgotten cabinets of his boyhood collection and was inspired to start collecting in earnest,<ref name=\":9\" /> his active interest dating from 1906.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bulletinofh112192122hill/page/n9|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1924|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=1|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> He used his resources to \"indulge a taste for collecting butterflies and [[moth]]s which remained with him throughout his life.\" He travelled \"in the East\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary \u2013 Mr. J. J. Joicey \u2013 Gifts to the Natural History Museum|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> as a young man and, although he employed experts to collect most of his specimens, also collected \"on his own account both here and abroad\"<ref name=\":9\" /> and \"travelled widely in Europe, India, China, Japan, Burma and America\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies. Death of an Eminent Naturalist|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Sheffield Independent|access-date=|page=5}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Who Was Who: 1929\u20131940|last=|first=|publisher=Adam & Charles Black|year=1960|isbn=|location=London|pages=722}}</ref> In 1913, he built and financed a private research museum, the Hill Museum, at his home in Witley, employing a [[curator]] and seven assistants.<ref name=\":1\" /> In one twelve-month period he collected some 17,000 specimens from across the world and was spending up to \u00a310,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=10000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) a year on the collection.<ref name=\":9\" /> Joicey said,\n\n<blockquote>How did I manage to spend \u00a310,000 a year on this collection? Well, these did not come from my back garden. I have had to send collectors to the far ends of the earth. ... When my work is done \u2013 that is, when I die \u2013 I will present the collection to the nation.<ref name=\":6\" />{{pb}}The work has been the ruling passion of my life, ... I don't think I am extravagant, as my researches and investigations will be of great value to the nation.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nJoicey became a fellow of the Zoological Society of London in 1890,<ref>{{Cite book|title=A List of the Fellows of the Zoological Society of London|last=|first=|publisher=William Clowes and Sons, Limited|year=1924|isbn=|location=London|pages=85}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Geographical Society in 1903,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1903|title=Meetings of the Royal Geographical Society, Sessions 1903\u20131904|url=https://archive.org/details/geographicaljou40britgoog/page/n744/mode/1up|journal=The Geographical Journal|volume=XXII|pages=709|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Entomological Society in 1908 (council member 1920\u20131923),<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1915roya/page/n23|title=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1915|last=|first=|publisher=Longmans, Green & Co.|year=1915|isbn=|location=London|pages=xix|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1912|title=Extracts from the Proceedings of the Royal Horticultural Society|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.240657/page/n779/mode/1up|journal=The Journal of the Royal Horticultural Society|volume=xxxviii|pages=xxii|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Linnean Society of London in 1913,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1914|title=December 4th, 1913|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsoflin191215linn/page/n174/mode/1up|journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society|volume=126|pages=3|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a life member of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France]] in 1921,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1931|title=Liste des membres de la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France arr\u00eat\u00e9e au 10 janvier 1930|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/bsef_0037-928x_1931_num_36_1_28972|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France|volume=36|issue=1|pages=XXVIII|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and a member of the [[London Natural History Society]] in 1928.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://archive.org/details/londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|journal=The London Naturalist|volume=1931|pages=38|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nAs well as amateur entomologist, Joicey was a well-known amateur [[Orchidaceae|orchidist]] and exhibited at meetings of the Royal Horticultural Society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey|journal=The Orchid Review|volume=40|pages=118|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\nJoicey could afford to build his collection of Lepidoptera through his family connection with the firm of \"Messrs. James Joicey & Co., Ltd, coalowners, Newcastle\", founded by his grandfather.<ref name=\"Major\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Major Joicey Dead. His Association with Local Coal Industry. Popular Turf Personality|last=|first=|date=24 January 1912|work=The Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|url-status=live|page=7}}</ref> Although described as having been \"nominally on the [[Stock exchange|Stock Exchange]] from 1896 to 1899\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Unable to Live on \u00a38,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=9 July 1910|work=Framlingham Weekly News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> then, in 1901, as a \"coal owner & ship owner\",<ref>1901 Census of England and Wales. RG12/814</ref> and, in 1913, as a director of the family coal mining firm,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=James Joicey & Co. Limited|last=|first=|date=1 December 1913|work=The Times|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> Joicey effectively had no occupation and throughout his life subsisted on substantial allowances from his parents. However, his income proved insufficient for his \"extravagance in living\" and the interest rates charged by money-lenders. Joicey became [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]] in 1909 with a deficiency of over \u00a3185,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=185000|start_year=1909|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}), and again in 1922 with a deficiency of over \u00a3430,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=430000|start_year=1922|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) despite his mother having given him \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1921|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in the interim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. In re Joicey|last=|first=|date=8 July 1910|work=The Times|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Borrowed Half a Million. Young Man's Dealings with Moneylenders|last=|first=|date=8 February 1922|work=Daily Mail|access-date=|url-status=live|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Millionaire's Son Again Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=10 February 1922|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref> The latter bankruptcy was discharged in October 1931.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey's Bankruptcy|last=|first=|date=16 October 1926|work=The Times|access-date=|page=4}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The son of a millionaire, for him money meant only one thing \u2013 more butterflies, still rarer specimens than he had already.\n| source = [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]], Joicey's head curator, 1932<ref name=\"Insects\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nJoicey's father, at one time a millionaire, had left over \u00a3700,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=700000|start_year=1912|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in his [[Estate (law)|estate]] in 1912, but his will ensured that no money went directly to his son.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Man Unable to Live on \u00a320,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Will of the Late Major W. J. Joicey|last=|first=|date=27 March 1912|work=Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|page=2}}</ref> The Witley house and estate were bought for Joicey after his first bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Wild Extravagance. Debts of \u00a3400,000 in Second Bankruptcy. Remarkable Figures|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Times|access-date=|page=12}}</ref> When sued by [[creditor]]<nowiki/>s in 1919, the judge said, \"He seems hardly to have grown up. He seems to have infantile tastes which his mother helps him gratify.\" When [[counsel]] stated that Joicey was \"susceptible to the wiles of the money-lenders\", the judge responded, \"And to the wiles of the butterflies.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. A Butterfly Collector and Moneylenders. Jacobs Brothers v. Joicey|last=|first=|date=31 March 1919|work=The Times|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> During the 1922 bankruptcy hearing, Joicey said, \"I think the money seems to have gone like snow in an oven.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Money Went Like Snow in Oven|last=|first=|date=7 March 1922|work=Pall Mall Gazette|access-date=|page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nJoicey's mother died in 1930, leaving an estate valued at over \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1930|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=Mary|date=1930|website=gov.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of his life, Joicey became an \"invalid\".<ref name=\"Insects\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a310,000 A Year for Butterflies \u2013 Insects Men Died to Get \u2013 Wonder Collection for Nation|last=|first=|date=15 March 1932|work=Dundee Evening Telegraph|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> He died of heart failure on 10 March 1932 at his home, The Hill, in Witley, Surrey, aged 61.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=21 March 1932|title=Milestones|url=|journal=Time Magazine|volume=XIX|issue=12|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Deaths|last=|first=|date=14 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He was buried at Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Arrangements for Today|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Joicey's estate was valued at \u00a31,151 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=1151|start_year=1932|r=-2|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=James John|date=1932|website=gov.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> his collection and museum having been principally paid for and owned by his mother.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Museum Bequest of Northern Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=7 June 1932|work=Sunderland Daily Echo and Shipping Gazette|access-date=|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Hambledon and Witley Estates|last=|first=|date=28 May 1932|work=The Surrey Advertiser and County Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The primary object of Mr. Joicey in making this collection of Lepidoptera is to advance in some way our scientific knowledge. ... The formation of a large collection has its value, because without access to plenty of material studies can only be incomplete and results are often erroneous. ... <br/>\nNo apology should be needed for amassing large collections ...\n| source = George Talbot, 1924<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|5}}\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nAs an adult, Joicey began collecting Lepidoptera in 1906{{Refn|According to Miller,<ref name=\"Miller\" /> Joicey first competed with [[Walter Rothschild]] to build the world's premier orchid collection but when Joicey went bankrupt the judge made him promise to abandon collecting orchids. However, the details of the anecdote do not match Joicey's known bankruptcies and the story is currently uncorroborated.|group=lower-alpha}} and by 1908 was advertising as far away as Australia for:\n\n<blockquote>Fresh-caught Specimens of Butterflies and Large Moths, in papers. Send Samples and state price per hundred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/163231414?searchTerm=%22james%20joicey%22|title=Wanted|last=|first=|date=30 December 1908|work=The Sydney Mail and New South Wales Advertiser|access-date=6 December 2019|page=1683}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe acquired the [[Henley Grose-Smith]] collection in 1910. Two years later he purchased the [[Herbert Druce]] collection. To house his growing collection, he founded the Hill Museum at his [[Witley]] home in 1913.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3}}<ref name=\":1\" /> Joicey employed curators, including [[Alfred Noakes]] (from 1906)<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Lance\u2013Corpl. Noakes Killed|last=|first=|date=20 November 1916|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=Proceedings of the Entomological Society of London for 1912: Wednesday, October 16th, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1912roya/page/n1141/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London|volume=1912|pages=xcvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and George Talbot (from 1915),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1954|title=President's Address. 28th January 1953|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingstrans19501953sout/page/62|journal=Proceedings and Transactions of the South London Entomological and Natural History Society|volume=1952\u201353|pages=62|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> with a staff of assistants.<ref name=\"Riley\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Society|last=|first=|date=8 August 1914|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BulletinHillMuseumPlate9.jpg|thumb|338x338px|New butterflies from [[Buru]] and [[New Guinea]]<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|592}} (Joicey Collection). Top left: [[Troides prattorum]]. Top right: [[Charaxes mars|Charaxes madensis]]. Both were described by Talbot at The Hill to a reporter in 1932 shortly after Joicey's death.<ref name=\"Insects\" />|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|left]]\n\nBetween 1913 and 1921 Joicey bought further collections: those of [[Ernst Suffert]], {{Circa|1913}}, [[Fritz Ludwig Otto Wichgraf]], 1913, [[Charles Swinhoe|Col. Charles Swinhoe]], 1916, [[Roland Trimen]], 1917, [[Charles George Nurse|Lt.-Col. C. G. Nurse]], 1919, [[Hamilton Herbert Druce|Hamilton Druce]], 1919, [[Heinrich Riffarth]], 1919, [[Henry John Elwes]], 1920, and [[Paul Dognin]], 1921. He added to these by sending special collectors to explore various regions on his behalf; for example, the [[Antwerp Edgar Pratt|Pratt family]] to [[South America]] and [[New Guinea]], and [[T. A. Barns]] to [[Central Africa]] (Barns dedicated his [[iarchive:wonderlandofeast00barnrich/page/n7|1922 book]] on the Eastern [[Belgian Congo|Congo]] to Joicey, his \"friend and patron\"). Mr. W. J. C. Frost, who visited the Islands of [[Tanimbar Islands|Tenimber]], Am, Key, [[Misool|Misol]], Obi and Sula during 1915\u20131918, donated his collection. Another collector, Mr. C. Talbot Bowring,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Weddings Today. Mr C. T. Bowring and Miss Parker|last=|first=|date=29 October 1908|work=The Globe|access-date=|page=8}}</ref> sent many thousands of specimens from Hainan Island (1918\u20131920).<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3\u20134}}\n\nIn 1916, when granting Joicey's curator conditional exemption from military service, [[Josceline Wodehouse|General Sir J. Wodehouse]] described the collection as \"probably the finest of its kind in England\", and Oxford professor [[Edward Bagnall Poulton|E. B. Poulton]] wrote that \"to leave the collection without a competent head would be a national disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Expensive Butterflies|last=|first=|date=31 August 1916|work=Illustrated Police News|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> \n\nIn 1919, the collection was valued at \u00a350,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=50000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}). It consisted of 1.5&nbsp;million specimens held in a room containing chests of drawers with \"5000 compartments neatly arranged round the room, and in addition 4000&nbsp;cases, all carefully labelled.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/star/1919/06/06/4|title=A Fortune for Butterflies. A Collector's Mania. Spends \u00a310,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=6 June 1919|work=The Star|access-date=20 November 2019|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> It was reported that,\n\n<blockquote>Here were butterflies of all sizes, of all colours \u2013 all arranged in an effective colour grouping. In one compartment were ... great winged beauties half a foot from wing tip to wing tip. In another were creatures so small that it needed a microscope to discern their beauty.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>\n\nAn annexe to the museum \"over eighty feet long by twenty feet wide\" (approximately 24 by 6&nbsp;m) was built in 1920.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|4}} In 1927 it was reported that the main building of the Museum was \"as large as a dance hall. The specimens are kept in special cabinets stacked almost to the roof. Here, all day long, Mr. Joicey and his assistants ... work at arranging and naming the fresh arrivals.\" Some specimens dated from the 1830s, others were obtained on the [[Henry Morton Stanley|Stanley]] expedition of 1871. Some were caught over 1,000&nbsp;miles (1,600&nbsp;km) from land, others had perished on the Alpine snowfields. They ranged in size from 1/2&nbsp;inch to 10&nbsp;inches (approximately 1&nbsp;cm to 25&nbsp;cm) wing spread.<ref name=\":9\" /> By 1930 the Hill Museum contained upwards of 380,000 specimens.<ref name=\"Riley\" />\n\n[[File:JJ Joicey butterfly cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum.jpg|thumb|Butterflies from the Joicey collection in a contemporary cabinet at the [http://www.haslemeremuseum.co.uk/ Haslemere Educational Museum].|alt=Photograph of multi-drawer butterfly display cabinet with some drawers open]]\n\nJoicey and his Hill Museum colleagues published more than 190 scientific articles on world Lepidoptera and \"produced some excellent work, especially on the Lepidoptera of New Guinea, [[Hainan]] Island, and Central and [[East Africa|Eastern Africa]].\"<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=Lee D.|date=1986|title=Presidential Address, 1984: A Tribute to the Amateur|url=http://images.peabody.yale.edu/lepsoc/jls/1980s/1986/1986-40(1)1-Miller.pdf|journal=Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society|volume=40|issue=1|pages=1\u20137|access-date=20 November 2019|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|4}} Joicey and Talbot co-edited four volumes of ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'', 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" /><ref name=\"Bulletin2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1928|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=2|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin3\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1929|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=3|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin4\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1932|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=4|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> and [[Alfred George Gabriel]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Many Local Names in New Year Honours List. Entomologist|last=|first=|date=9 January 1958|work=Harrow Observer|access-date=|url-status=live|page=9}}</ref> published ''A Catalogue of the Type Specimens of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum'' in 1932.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDuring his lifetime, Joicey \"presented to the Nation\" between 200,000 and 300,000 Lepidoptera specimens including about 75,000 to the Natural History Museum. The latter figure included 15,500 moths and a number butterflies (1923), his whole collection of over 30,000 [[Skipper (butterfly)|Hesperiidae]] butterflies (1926), 6,000 [[Lymantriinae|Lymantriidae]] moths (1928), and, in 1931, a series of 800 [[Type (biology)|type]] butterflies being \"the most valuable, both scientifically and intrinsically ... received for the past two decades\", some thousands of moths including over 600 type and [[paratype]] moths, and 1,500 butterflies including 750 type specimens. In 1932, the collection numbered over 500,000 specimens.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0|title=A Catalogue of Manuscripts in the Entomology Library of the Natural History Museum, London|last=Harvey|first=Julie M.V.|last2=Gilbert|first2=Pamela|last3=Martin|first3=Kathy|publisher=Mansell Publishing Limited|year=1996|isbn=0-7201-2290-2|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0/page/114 114]\u2013115|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Sale Room \u2013 Joicey Collection|last=|first=|date=29 April 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>\n\nHowever, shortly after Joicey's death in 1932 the Hill Museum was closed and the property sold by his mother's [[executor]]s.<ref name=\":5\" /> Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>The closing of the Hill Museum and the disbanding of its staff are events which will have serious repercussions throughout the ranks of lepidopterists in all parts of the world, and will definitely retard the advance of this science. In a comparatively short space of time Mr Joicey accomplished much for his favourite study.<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}</blockquote>\n\n<gallery caption=\"The Hill Museum\">\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumExterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of the outside of building with four arched windows|Hill Museum: Exterior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumAnnexe.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a long single-story barracks hut in a field|Hill Museum: Annexe\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumInterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a room crowded with display cabinets and work benches|Hill Museum: A part of the interior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumPhotomicrography.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of man adjusting photographic equipment on a bench|Hill Museum: Photomicrographic Department under Mr. H. J. Campbell\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1923.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of six gentlemen standing outside on pathway stairs|Joicey (second from left) and other entomologists at the Hill Museum in 1920\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Joicey Collection examples\">\nFile:BMNH(E)983480 Delias joiceyi Talb. female3 ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Delias]] joiceyi''\nFile:BMNH(E)983400 Delias maudei J.&N. male ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias maudei''\nFile:BMNH(E)141732 Delias mariae J.&T. AT female ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias mariae''\nFile:Ornithoptera goliath samson f. joiceyi Noakes & Talbot, 1915.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Ornithoptera goliath]] samson'' f. ''joiceyi''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0649.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''Ornithoptera joyceyi'' (male), two ''Delias''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0651.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of a butterfly specimen|''Ornithoptera joiceyi'' (female)\nFile:DeudorixMaudeiMFJoiceyTalbot1916.JPG|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Deudorix]] maudei''\nFile:Deudorix littoralis TypesMFUpAC1.jpg|alt=Photograph of two pinned butterflies with notes above|''Deudorix littoralis'' (male & female types)\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea and Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VIII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate IX.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New butterflies from Buru and New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate X.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New [[Sphingidae]]\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate XI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New Sphingidae\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate XII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New [[Zygaenidae]]\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0665 with explanation.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Milionia]]'', four others\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14.jpg|alt=Photograph of a drawer of pinned butterflies|South American ''[[Papilio]]''\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14 close-up.jpg|alt=Photograph of pinned butterflies with notes under each|South American ''Papilio'' (detail)    \n</gallery>\n\n==Legacy==\nJoicey's Hill Museum produced over 190 research articles which were published in a range of scientific journals.<ref name=\"Riley\" /> In 1934, the Natural History Museum received more than 300,000 specimens as part of the Joicey Bequest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Museum: Gift of Butterfly Collection|last=|first=|date=27 March 1934|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Together with the [[Charles Oberth\u00fcr|Oberth\u00fcr]] and [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] collections, the Joicey collection contributed to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the Natural History Museum, London.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Miller\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/collections/entomology-collections/lepidoptera-collections.html|title=Lepidoptera collections|last=|first=|date=|website=National History Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=9 April 1932|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=129|issue=3258|pages=535|doi=10.1038/129535a0|access-date=22 November 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nA report in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>During his life-time, the late J. J. Joicey probably did more to stimulate the study of butterflies and moths, especially those of Africa, than any other private individual in Great Britain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=31 March 1934|title=Recent Acquisitions at the Natural History Museum|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/133490b0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=133|issue=3361|pages=490|doi=10.1038/133490b0|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Works==\n===Joicey and Talbot (partial list)===\n{{div col}}\n*New Species of Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''15''' (87): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/295|295\u2013301]], pl. [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/n662/mode/1up|XII]] (1915)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Dutch New Guinea (with A. Noakes). ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''63''' (3,4): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/361/mode/1up|361\u2013386]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/n587|LV\u2013LXII]] (1916)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Schouten Islands. ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''64''' (1): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/65/mode/1up|65\u201383]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/n151|3\u20136]] (1916)\n*New Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (115): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/50|50\u201387]], pls [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/n484/mode/1up|1\u20134]] (1917)\n*New Lepidoptera from Waigeu, Dutch New Guinea and Biak. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (117): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/216|216\u2013229]] (1917)\n*New South-American Rhopalocera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/259/mode/1up|259\u2013264]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New South-American Arctiidae. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/265/mode/1up|265\u2013270]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New butterflies from Africa and the east. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/271/mode/1up|271\u2013272]] (1918)\n*A Gynandromorph of ''Papilio lycophron'' Hbn. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/273/mode/1up|273]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n379/mode/1up|II]] (1918)\n*Three Aberrations of Lepidoptera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/275/mode/1up|275\u2013276]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New forms of Indo-Australian butterflies. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''1''' (3): [https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/565/mode/1up 565\u2013569] (1924)\n*New forms of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. ''Encyclopedia of Entomology'' (B III Lepidoptera) '''2''': 1\u201314 (1926)\n*New forms of Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''2''' (1): [[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n29|19\u201327]] (1928)\n*Also see the [http://bionames.org/authors/J%20J%20Joicey BioNames database] linking taxonomic names to their original descriptions\n{{div col end}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The majority of the papers are of a purely [[Systematics|systematic]] nature, consisting of the description of new [[species]] or the revision of various [[Genus|genera]]; but there are several of principally [[Fauna|faunistic]] interest, as, for example, the Catalogue of the Lepidoptera of Hainan. They represent a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value.\n| source = Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'', 1932<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\n===Associated with the Hill Museum===\n'''''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum''''' (111 articles and 80 plates<ref name=\"Riley\" />)\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n12/mode/1up 1921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n13/mode/2up 1921\u20131924]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n15/mode/2up 1924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n7/mode/2up|1928]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n7/mode/2up|1929]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n7/mode/1up|1931]]\n\n'''''Other journals''''' (82 articles<ref name=\"Riley\" />) (partial list)\n\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/13/mode/1up 1914\u20131916]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/14/mode/2up 1916\u20131921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/572/mode/1up 1921\u20131924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n207/mode/2up|1924\u20131927]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Summaries==\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomological News'' '''43''': [[iarchive:entomologicalnew42amer/page/140/mode/1up|140]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''London Naturalist'' '''1931''': [[iarchive:londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|38]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Nature'' '''129''': [https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf 535], [https://www.nature.com/articles/129896a0.pdf 896]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.]  ''Orchid Review'' '''40''': [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey 118]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.] ''The Times'' (16 March) p.&nbsp;9\n*Gilbert, P.  2000: ''Butterfly Collectors and Painters: Four Centuries of Colour Plates from the Library Collections of the Natural History Museum, London''. Singapore, Beaumont Publishing Pte Ltd: X+166 S, pp. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WQBNAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Butterfly+Collectors+and+Painters.+Four+centuries+of+colour+plates+from+The+Library+Collections+of+The+Natural+History+Museum%2C+London.%22&q=joicey 31]\u201333\n*Riley, N. D. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist'' '''65''': 142\u2013144\n*Turner, H. J. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist's Record & Journal of Variation'' '''44''': [[iarchive:entomologistsr441932tutt/page/68/mode/1up|68]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=James John Joicey}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/205188852/james-john-joicey Grave site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joicey, James John}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:British entomologists]]\n[[Category:English lepidopterists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Entomological Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Zoological Society of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of