{"title_page": "Marc Jampole", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Marc Jampole\n| image         =\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =\t\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1950|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Public Relations Executive]] <br> [[Poet]] <br> [[Television news reporter]]\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| period      =\n| genre       =\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Marc Jampole''' (born July 24, 1950) is an American [[poet]], public relations executive, former television news reporter and political blogger.\n\n==Background and education==\nIn the 1970s, Jampole taught French and German language and literature and filmmaking at the University of Washington.  He also made several avant-garde films that were shown at a number of independent film festivals.<ref name=\"interview\">[http://www.cervenabarvapress.com/MarcJampoleinterview.htm \"Interview with Marc Jampole\", Cervena Barva Press]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJampole formed Jampole Communications, Inc. in 1989.  As principal, Jampole wrote more than 1,800 articles and was a well-known speaker on media-relations and crisis communications. He was frequently quoted in the mass media as a public relations expert.<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Smashing Myths: Many public relations people are headed in the wrong direction.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' November 23, 2004.[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04328/415961-28.stm]</ref><ref>Sostek, Anya. \"Occupy Movement presents tricky public relations challenge for targeted companies.\"  ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' October 30, 2011. [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/region/occupy-movement-presents-tricky-public-relations-challenge-for-targeted-companies-36309/]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Companies should employ strategies to overcome bankruptcy stigma.\" ''Pittsburgh Business Times.'' December 3, 2001. [http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2001/12/03/focus4.html]</ref><ref>Lindeman, Teresa. \"Some criticize Target's response to breach as too slow.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' December 20, 2013. [http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2013/12/20/Target-security-breach-affects-up-to-40-million-accounts-Target-victimized-by-major-security-breach/stories/201312200066]</ref>  Jampole also developed communications plans for more than 100 crises and handled three of the largest [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcies in American history - the bankruptcy of Allegheny International and two [[Penn Traffic Company]] bankruptcies.<ref>Goins, Tony. \"Penn Traffic closing five local Big Bear stores.\" ''Columbus Business First.'' October 10, 2003. [http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/10/06/daily36.html]</ref> At the end of 2016, Jampole sold the operations of Jampole Communications to Pittsburgh-based Wordwrite Communications,  where he serves as executive vice president.\u201d<ref>Tascarella, Patty. \u201cLongtime Pittsburgh PR agencies combining.\u201d Pittsburgh Business Times. November 30, 2016</ref>\n\nJampole has written for many publications, including [[Jewish Currents]], Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute, American Book Review, The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, NonProfit World, Industry Week, American Banker, Hospital News, Small Business News and many other journals and newspapers. He serves on the editorial board of Jewish Currents and is currently its president. <ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Class Warfare from the Mid-'30s until Today\" ''Jewish Currents.'' February 18, 2014. [http://jewishcurrents.org/class-warfare-mid-30s-today-25019]</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\n\nJampole has published two books of poetry, ''Music From Words'' (Bellday Books 2007) and ''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017).<ref name=\"bellday\">Jampole, Marc.  ''Music from Words'' Bellday Books 2007. [www.belldaybooks.com]</ref> His poems have been published in many poetry journals and anthologies, including ''[[The Mississippi Review']]',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Dot & Sylvia.\" ''The Mississippi Review'' Vol. 31 #1-2. Spring 2003. {{cite web|url=https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID%3D268 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719010422/https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID=268 |archivedate=2010-07-19 }}</ref> ''The Evansville Review'', ''[[The Courtland Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \u201cInstead of Sex.\u201d ''The Courtland Review'' Issue 46. Feb 2010. [http://www.cortlandreview.com/issue/46/jampole.html?ref=home]</ref> ''Vallum'', ''Cutthroat'', [[Slant Magazine]], ''Illumen'', ''[[Oxford Magazine]]'', ''Janus Head'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"These Are a Few,\" \"Divine Amnesia,\" \"A Brother's Funeral.\" ''Janus Head'' #74 \"Addiction 2\". 2004. {{cite web|url=http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830154112/http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-30 }}</ref> ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (2005 Bayeaux Arts Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"If Nature had a Conscious.\" ''Only the Sea Keeps.'' Bayeaux Arts Press. 2005.</ref> ''[[Wilderness House Literary Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Garbo at 48.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 2 #4. Winter 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-2.4/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"At the Cocktail Party,\" \"On Manhattan Beach with Love and Thanatos.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 3 #1. Spring 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-3.1/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref> ''Ellipsis'',<ref>[http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf Jampole, Marc. \"The Wrestler\" ''Ellipsis'' #44.  Spring 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723003242/http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf |date=2012-07-23 }}</ref> ''Journey'' (2009 Eden Waters Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"A Modern Passion.\" ''Journey.'' Eden Waters Press. 2009.[http://edenwaterspress.com/current_issue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314071733/http://www.edenwaterspress.com/current_issue |date=2012-03-14 }}</ref> and ''Acapella Zoo'',<ref>[http://www.acappellazoo.com/fall08.5 Jampole, Marc. \"The Walk Away.\" ''Acapella Zoo'' #1. Fall 2008]</ref> among others.  Four of his poems were nominated for the [[Pushcart Prize]],'' one in 1990, and three in ''2008.<ref name=\"bellday\" />''\n\n''Slant: A Journal of Poetry'' references Marc Jampole as a poet whose work verges on the experimental or brash.<ref>[http://uca.edu/english/slant-a-journal-of-poetry/ \"Slant: A Journal of Poetry.\" University of Central Arkansas.]</ref></blockquote>\n\nJampole's work is rarely autobiographical.<ref name=\"interview\" /> The narrators in his poems are sometimes famous people, biblical or historical figures mes ordinary people at a point of epiphany or anagnorisis. In one poem, a real-estate agent who thinks he's [[Moses]] sees the burning bush in an upscale suburb. In others, [[Gilgamesh]] gets caught in a traffic jam, [[Blaise Pascal]] faces a crisis of faith and faith in reason, a former whiz kid disassociates into psychosis and [[Hugo Ball]], one of the founders of the Dada movement, sells his wife to soldiers.<ref name=\"bellday\" /> He also writes in reaction to world events, such as the 2004 tsunami in Southeast Asia.<ref>Behe, Regis. \"Tsunami project reveals quality of poetry in Pittsburgh area.\" ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review.'' December 25, 2005.[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_407023.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218085628/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/S_407023.html |date=2010-02-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Music from Words'' (Bellday Books 2007)\n*''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017)\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''The Great American Wise Ass Poetry Anthology'' (2016)\n* ''And Love'' (Jacar Press 2012)\n* ''Fusion of Form'' (2009)\n* ''Bagel Bards IV'' (2009) and V (2010)\n* ''Natural Language'' (Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh 2010)\n* ''Journey'' (Eden Waters Press 2009)\n* ''A Poet's Haggadah'' (Ain't Got No Press 2008)\n* ''Along These Rivers'' (Quadrant Publishing 2008)\n* ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (Bayeaux Arts 2005)\n\n===Literary publications===\n* ''580 Split''\n* ''Acapella Zoo''\n*''ALTE''\n*''Barrow Street''\n* ''Big City Lit''\n*''Blue Unicorn''\n* ''China Grove''\n*''Connecticut River Review''\n* ''[[Cortland Review]]''\n* ''Curbside Review''\n* ''Cutthroat''\n* ''Ellipsis''\n*''Ibbetson Street''\n* ''Illumen''\n* ''Janus Head''\n* ''[[Jewish Currents]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/unionized-public-schools-do-a-better-job/|title=Unionized Public Schools Do a Better Job, But Poverty trumps Teachers Everywhere|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/paul-celan-as-existentialist-poet/|title=Paul Celan as Existentialist Poet|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=2016|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Licking Review Review''\n*''Literary Hatchet''\n* ''Main Street Rag''\n* ''Miracle''\n* ''[[Mississippi Review]]''\n* ''Orphic Lute''\n* ''[[Oxford Magazine]]''\n* ''Paper Street''\n* ''Peralta Press''\n* ''Pittsburgh Poetry Review''\n* ''Pittsburgh Quarterly''\n* ''Rat\u2019s Ass Review''\n* ''Recours au Po\u00e9me''\n* ''Rune''\n* ''Sin Fronteras''\n* ''Slant: A Journal of Poetry''\n* ''The Evansville Review''\n* ''Vallum''\n*''Vox Populi''\n* ''White Pelican Review''\n* ''[[Wilderness House Review]]''\n* ''Yawp!''\n\n===Films===\n*''Tinbad- 1973''\n*''Preludes- 1974''\n*''Judgement of Paris- 1975''\n*''Landscapes of Desire - 2012''\n\n=== OpEdge Blog ===\nJampole has written the OpEdge<sup>TM</sup> blog since 2019. OpEdge discusses the political and social issues of the day from a left-wing point of view, often using academic and secondary research to make the case for his views, including raising taxes on the wealthy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/another-proof-we-need-to-tax-the-wealthy-more-funds-for-investing-in-guitars-stamps/]|title=\u201cAnother proof we need to tax the wealthy more: funds for investing in guitars & stamps.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 25, 2013|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/new-tax-bill-tries-something-thats-already-failed-many-times-lowering-taxes-on-wealthy-to-spur-economic-growth-but-its-typical-of-gop-to-propose-programs-that-have-proven-not-to-wo/|title=New tax bill tries something that\u2019s already failed many times.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 21, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/if-the-goal-is-a-strong-economy-tax-reform-should-lower-taxes-on-poor-raise-them-on-wealthy/|title=\u201cIf the goal is a strong economy, tax reform should lower taxes on the wealthy and rise them on wealthy.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, cutting the military budget<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/u-s-spends-40-of-worlds-total-military-budget-its-controlled-by-an-inconsistent-bellicose-ignoramus-who-favors-disruption-over-working-together-shows-no-regard-for/|title=\u201cU.S. spends 40% of world\u2019s total military budget & it\u2019s controlled by an inconsistent & bellicose ignoramus.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 17, 2018|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/why-is-all-the-talk-about-cutting-payments-to-the-poor-and-elderly-how-about-cutting-defense/|title=\u201cWhy is all the talk about cutting payments to the poor and elderly. How about cutting defense?\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 11, 2012|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and turning away from the celebrity-fueled culture of consumption<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/the-commercialization-of-halloween-has-helped-further-the-infantilization-of-american-culture/|title=\u201cThe commercialization of Haloween has helped further the infantilization of American culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/you-can-ignore-the-royal-wedding-but-not-the-overwhelming-presence-of-celebrity-culture/|title=\u201cYou can ignore the royal wedding, but not he overwhelming presence of celebrity culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 25, 2011|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. National Public Radio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=510628831?storyId=510628831|title=\u201cComic Hero: Why Donald Trump\u2019s Candid Rhetoric Resonates with Supporters.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 19, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and other media have frequently quoted or referenced OpEdge articles. OpEdge articles also often appears on the websites of ''The Progressive Populist''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/|title=OpEdge|last=|first=|date=|website=The Progressive Populist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'', Jewish Currents''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-making-of-our-tables-one-table/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Making of Our Tables One Table.|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 29, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-truth-vs-republican-whitewashing/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Truth versus Republican Brainwashing.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 16, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-taxes-and-the-politics-of-crass-selfishness/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Taxes and the Politics of Crass Selfishness.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=November 29, 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'',''and Vox Populi.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jampole, Marc}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Marc Jampole\n| image         =\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     =\t\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1950|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Public Relations Executive]] <br> [[Poet]] <br> [[Television news reporter]]\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| period      =\n| genre       =\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Marc Jampole''' (born July 24, 1950) is an American [[poet]], public relations executive, former television news reporter and political blogger.\n\n==Background and education==\nIn the 1970s, Jampole taught French and German language and literature and filmmaking at the University of Washington.  He also made several avant-garde films that were shown at a number of independent film festivals.<ref name=\"interview\">[http://www.cervenabarvapress.com/MarcJampoleinterview.htm \"Interview with Marc Jampole\", Cervena Barva Press]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJampole formed Jampole Communications, Inc. in 1989.  As principal, Jampole wrote more than 1,800 articles and was a well-known speaker on media-relations and crisis communications. He was frequently quoted in the mass media as a public relations expert.<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Smashing Myths: Many public relations people are headed in the wrong direction.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' November 23, 2004.[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04328/415961-28.stm]</ref><ref>Sostek, Anya. \"Occupy Movement presents tricky public relations challenge for targeted companies.\"  ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' October 30, 2011. [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/region/occupy-movement-presents-tricky-public-relations-challenge-for-targeted-companies-36309/]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Companies should employ strategies to overcome bankruptcy stigma.\" ''Pittsburgh Business Times.'' December 3, 2001. [http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2001/12/03/focus4.html]</ref><ref>Lindeman, Teresa. \"Some criticize Target's response to breach as too slow.\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' December 20, 2013. [http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2013/12/20/Target-security-breach-affects-up-to-40-million-accounts-Target-victimized-by-major-security-breach/stories/201312200066]</ref>  Jampole also developed communications plans for more than 100 crises and handled three of the largest [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcies in American history - the bankruptcy of Allegheny International and two [[Penn Traffic Company]] bankruptcies.<ref>Goins, Tony. \"Penn Traffic closing five local Big Bear stores.\" ''Columbus Business First.'' October 10, 2003. [http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/10/06/daily36.html]</ref> At the end of 2016, Jampole sold the operations of Jampole Communications to Pittsburgh-based Wordwrite Communications,  where he serves as executive vice president.\u201d<ref>Tascarella, Patty. \u201cLongtime Pittsburgh PR agencies combining.\u201d Pittsburgh Business Times. November 30, 2016</ref>\n\nJampole has written for many publications, including [[Jewish Currents]], Journal of the American Bankruptcy Institute, American Book Review, The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, NonProfit World, Industry Week, American Banker, Hospital News, Small Business News and many other journals and newspapers. He serves on the editorial board of Jewish Currents and is currently its president. <ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Class Warfare from the Mid-'30s until Today\" ''Jewish Currents.'' February 18, 2014. [http://jewishcurrents.org/class-warfare-mid-30s-today-25019]</ref>\n\n==Poetry==\n\nJampole has published two books of poetry, ''Music From Words'' (Bellday Books 2007) and ''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017).<ref name=\"bellday\">Jampole, Marc.  ''Music from Words'' Bellday Books 2007. [www.belldaybooks.com]</ref> His poems have been published in many poetry journals and anthologies, including ''[[The Mississippi Review']]',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Dot & Sylvia.\" ''The Mississippi Review'' Vol. 31 #1-2. Spring 2003. {{cite web|url=https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID%3D268 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719010422/https://shop.usm.edu/ustores/web/product_detail.jsp?PRODUCTID=268 |archivedate=2010-07-19 }}</ref> ''The Evansville Review'', ''[[The Courtland Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \u201cInstead of Sex.\u201d ''The Courtland Review'' Issue 46. Feb 2010. [http://www.cortlandreview.com/issue/46/jampole.html?ref=home]</ref> ''Vallum'', ''Cutthroat'', [[Slant Magazine]], ''Illumen'', ''[[Oxford Magazine]]'', ''Janus Head'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"These Are a Few,\" \"Divine Amnesia,\" \"A Brother's Funeral.\" ''Janus Head'' #74 \"Addiction 2\". 2004. {{cite web|url=http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830154112/http://www.janushead.org/7-1/Jampole.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-30 }}</ref> ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (2005 Bayeaux Arts Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"If Nature had a Conscious.\" ''Only the Sea Keeps.'' Bayeaux Arts Press. 2005.</ref> ''[[Wilderness House Literary Review]]'',<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"Garbo at 48.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 2 #4. Winter 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-2.4/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref><ref>Jampole, Marc. \"At the Cocktail Party,\" \"On Manhattan Beach with Love and Thanatos.\" ''Wilderness House Review'' Vol. 3 #1. Spring 2008. [http://www.whlreview.com/no-3.1/poetry/MarcJampole.pdf]</ref> ''Ellipsis'',<ref>[http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf Jampole, Marc. \"The Wrestler\" ''Ellipsis'' #44.  Spring 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723003242/http://www.westminstercollege.edu/ellipsis/archives/Ellipsis2008.pdf |date=2012-07-23 }}</ref> ''Journey'' (2009 Eden Waters Press),<ref>Jampole, Marc. \"A Modern Passion.\" ''Journey.'' Eden Waters Press. 2009.[http://edenwaterspress.com/current_issue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314071733/http://www.edenwaterspress.com/current_issue |date=2012-03-14 }}</ref> and ''Acapella Zoo'',<ref>[http://www.acappellazoo.com/fall08.5 Jampole, Marc. \"The Walk Away.\" ''Acapella Zoo'' #1. Fall 2008]</ref> among others.  Four of his poems were nominated for the [[Pushcart Prize]],'' one in 1990, and three in ''2008.<ref name=\"bellday\" />''\n\n''Slant: A Journal of Poetry'' references Marc Jampole as a poet whose work verges on the experimental or brash.<ref>[http://uca.edu/english/slant-a-journal-of-poetry/ \"Slant: A Journal of Poetry.\" University of Central Arkansas.]</ref></blockquote>\n\nJampole's work is rarely autobiographical.<ref name=\"interview\" /> The narrators in his poems are sometimes famous people, biblical or historical figures mes ordinary people at a point of epiphany or anagnorisis. In one poem, a real-estate agent who thinks he's [[Moses]] sees the burning bush in an upscale suburb. In others, [[Gilgamesh]] gets caught in a traffic jam, [[Blaise Pascal]] faces a crisis of faith and faith in reason, a former whiz kid disassociates into psychosis and [[Hugo Ball]], one of the founders of the Dada movement, sells his wife to soldiers.<ref name=\"bellday\" /> He also writes in reaction to world events, such as the 2004 tsunami in Southeast Asia.<ref>Behe, Regis. \"Tsunami project reveals quality of poetry in Pittsburgh area.\" ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review.'' December 25, 2005.[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_407023.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218085628/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/S_407023.html |date=2010-02-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Music from Words'' (Bellday Books 2007)\n*''Cubist States of Mind/Not the Cruelest Month'' (Poet's Haven Press 2017)\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''The Great American Wise Ass Poetry Anthology'' (2016)\n* ''And Love'' (Jacar Press 2012)\n* ''Fusion of Form'' (2009)\n* ''Bagel Bards IV'' (2009) and V (2010)\n* ''Natural Language'' (Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh 2010)\n* ''Journey'' (Eden Waters Press 2009)\n* ''A Poet's Haggadah'' (Ain't Got No Press 2008)\n* ''Along These Rivers'' (Quadrant Publishing 2008)\n* ''Only the Sea Keeps'' (Bayeaux Arts 2005)\n\n===Literary publications===\n* ''580 Split''\n* ''Acapella Zoo''\n*''ALTE''\n*''Barrow Street''\n* ''Big City Lit''\n*''Blue Unicorn''\n* ''China Grove''\n*''Connecticut River Review''\n* ''[[Cortland Review]]''\n* ''Curbside Review''\n* ''Cutthroat''\n* ''Ellipsis''\n*''Ibbetson Street''\n* ''Illumen''\n* ''Janus Head''\n* ''[[Jewish Currents]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/unionized-public-schools-do-a-better-job/|title=Unionized Public Schools Do a Better Job, But Poverty trumps Teachers Everywhere|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Licking Review Review''\n*''Literary Hatchet''\n* ''Main Street Rag''\n* ''Miracle''\n* ''[[Mississippi Review]]''\n* ''Orphic Lute''\n* ''[[Oxford Magazine]]''\n* ''Paper Street''\n* ''Peralta Press''\n* ''Pittsburgh Poetry Review''\n* ''Pittsburgh Quarterly''\n* ''Rat\u2019s Ass Review''\n* ''Recours au Po\u00e9me''\n* ''Rune''\n* ''Sin Fronteras''\n* ''Slant: A Journal of Poetry''\n* ''The Evansville Review''\n* ''Vallum''\n*''Vox Populi''\n* ''White Pelican Review''\n* ''[[Wilderness House Review]]''\n* ''Yawp!''\n\n===Films===\n*''Tinbad- 1973''\n*''Preludes- 1974''\n*''Judgement of Paris- 1975''\n*''Landscapes of Desire - 2012''\n\n=== OpEdge Blog ===\nJampole has written the OpEdge<sup>TM</sup> blog since 2019. OpEdge discusses the political and social issues of the day from a left-wing point of view, often using academic and secondary research to make the case for his views, including raising taxes on the wealthy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/another-proof-we-need-to-tax-the-wealthy-more-funds-for-investing-in-guitars-stamps/]|title=\u201cAnother proof we need to tax the wealthy more: funds for investing in guitars & stamps.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 25, 2013|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/new-tax-bill-tries-something-thats-already-failed-many-times-lowering-taxes-on-wealthy-to-spur-economic-growth-but-its-typical-of-gop-to-propose-programs-that-have-proven-not-to-wo/|title=New tax bill tries something that\u2019s already failed many times.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 21, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/if-the-goal-is-a-strong-economy-tax-reform-should-lower-taxes-on-poor-raise-them-on-wealthy/|title=\u201cIf the goal is a strong economy, tax reform should lower taxes on the wealthy and rise them on wealthy.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=September 18, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, cutting the military budget<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/u-s-spends-40-of-worlds-total-military-budget-its-controlled-by-an-inconsistent-bellicose-ignoramus-who-favors-disruption-over-working-together-shows-no-regard-for/|title=\u201cU.S. spends 40% of world\u2019s total military budget & it\u2019s controlled by an inconsistent & bellicose ignoramus.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=August 17, 2018|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/why-is-all-the-talk-about-cutting-payments-to-the-poor-and-elderly-how-about-cutting-defense/|title=\u201cWhy is all the talk about cutting payments to the poor and elderly. How about cutting defense?\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=December 11, 2012|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and turning away from the celebrity-fueled culture of consumption<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/the-commercialization-of-halloween-has-helped-further-the-infantilization-of-american-culture/|title=\u201cThe commercialization of Haloween has helped further the infantilization of American culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=October 30, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jampole.com/blog/you-can-ignore-the-royal-wedding-but-not-the-overwhelming-presence-of-celebrity-culture/|title=\u201cYou can ignore the royal wedding, but not he overwhelming presence of celebrity culture.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=April 25, 2011|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. National Public Radio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=510628831?storyId=510628831|title=\u201cComic Hero: Why Donald Trump\u2019s Candid Rhetoric Resonates with Supporters.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=January 19, 2017|website=OpEdge|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and other media have frequently quoted or referenced OpEdge articles. OpEdge articles also often appears on the websites of ''The Progressive Populist''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://progressivepopulist.blogspot.com/|title=OpEdge|last=|first=|date=|website=The Progressive Populist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'', Jewish Currents''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-making-of-our-tables-one-table/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Making of Our Tables One Table.|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 29, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-truth-vs-republican-whitewashing/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Truth versus Republican Brainwashing.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=March 16, 2018|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.jewishcurrents.org/opedge-taxes-and-the-politics-of-crass-selfishness/|title=\u201cOpEdge: Taxes and the Politics of Crass Selfishness.\u201d|last=Jampole|first=Marc|date=November 29, 2017|website=Jewish Currents|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'',''and Vox Populi.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jampole, Marc}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[C