{"title_page": "Joint Committee Against Communism", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Joint Committee Against Communism\n| pronounce           = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| named_after         = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = \n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = <!-- use {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> January 1950\n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> late 1950s?\n| founder             = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz\n| founding_location   = [[New York City]]\n| merger              = \n| type                = \n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = \n| headquarters        =\n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = \n| services            = \n| methods             = \n| fields              = \n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| language            = \n| sec_gen             = \n| leader_title        = Chairman\n| leader_name         = [[Alfred Kohlberg]]\n| leader_title2       = Executive Director\n| leader_name2        = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz\n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = Theodore Kirkpatrick, [[Roy Cohn]]\n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)]]'', ''[[Red Channels]]'' newsletter, ''[[Plain Talk]]'' magazine\n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\nThe '''Joint Committee Against Communism''', also known as the '''Joint Committee Against Communism in New York''', was an [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]] organization during the 1950s.<ref name=Krause>\n{{cite journal\n| first1 = Allen\n| last1 = Krause\n| title = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz and the American Jewish League Against Communism:  From McCarthy to Mississippi\n| journal = Southern Jewish History\n| publisher = Southern Jewish Historical Society\n| url = https://www.academia.edu/41725935/Allen_Krause_Rabbi_Benjamin_Schultz_and_the_American_Jewish_League_Against_Communism_From_McCarthy_to_Mississippi\n| pages = 167 (quote), 208 (fn25 on founding)\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=SJH>\n{{cite journal\n| first1 = Allen\n| last1 = Krause\n| title = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz and the American Jewish League Against Communism:  From McCarthy to Mississippi\n| journal = Southern Jewish History\n| publisher = Southern Jewish Historical Society\n| url = https://www.jewishsouth.org/index-authors\n| pages = \n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Beim>\n{{cite journal\n| first1 = Aaron\n| last1 = Beim\n| first2 = Gary Alan\n| last2 = Fine\n| title = The Cultural Framework of Prejudice:  Reputational Images and the Postwar Disjuncture of Jews and Communism\n| journal = The Sociological Quarterly\n| publisher = Taylor & Francies\n| url = https://www.jstor.org/stable/40220030?seq=1\n| pages = 373\u2013397\n| date = 1997\n| accessdate = 2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Lyons-Eugene-1940.jpg|thumb|right|[[Eugene Lyons]] (1940) was a co-founder of the committee's core coalition member, American Jewish League Against Communism, Inc. (AJLAC)]]\n[[Benjamin Schultz]] of [[Rochester, New York]], had studied under Rabbi [[Stephen S. Wise]] at the Jewish Institute of Religion in New York City.  He was ordained as a rabbi in 1931 and served a Reform congregation, Temple Emanu-El in [[Yonkers, New York]].  From October 14 to 16, 1947, Schultz published a series of articles in the ''[[New York World-Telegram]]'' on Communism among Protestant and Catholic churches and Jewish synagogues.  He attacked the Reverend Dr. [[Harry F. Ward]] of [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]], [[Abraham Cronbach]] of [[Hebrew Union College]], and Stephen S. Wise by name.<ref name=Krause/>\n\nOn March 15, 1948, Schultz announced in the ''New York Times'' the founding of the American Jewish League Against Communism, Inc. (AJLAC).  AJLAC claimed to side with an \"overwhelming majority of American Jewry\" against Communism.  It praised [[David Dubinsky]], [[Abraham Cahan]], [[Walter Winchell]], and [[David Lawrence (publisher)|David Lawrence]].  Schultz declared, \"Zionism and communism are incompatible.\"<ref name=Judges>\n{{cite book\n| first = Merle\n| last = Miller\n| title = The Judges and the Judged\n| publisher = Doublday\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wM9AAAAAIAAJ\n| page = 153 (AJLAC), 154 (Muir), 155, 156 (Levine), 157 (Roosevelt, ADA), 178 (Old Man Atom)\n| date = 1952\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  Headquartered at 220 West Forty-second Street, AJLAC sought to remove \"all Communist activity in Jewish life, wherever it may be.\"<ref name=Unit>\n{{cite news\n| title = \"Jewish Unit Vows Communist Purge\" \n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/15/archives/jewish-unit-vows-communist-purge-league-forms-here-to-ferret-out.html \n| page = 7\n| date = 15 March 1948\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAJLAC national organizing members included:\n* Benjamin Schultz (executive director)\n* [[Alfred Kohlberg]] (chairman), listed as \"head of the board of directors of the American-China Policy Association, Inc.\"\n* Harry Pasternak, retired realtor (treasurer)\n* [[Benjamin Gitlow]], former general secretary of the [[Communist Party USA]]\n* [[George Sokolsky]], nationally syndicated columnist\n* [[Eugene Lyons]], nationally syndicated columnist\n* [[Isaac Don Levine]], nationally syndicated columnist and editor of ''[[Plain Talk]]''\n* Rabbi David S. Savitz\n* Rabbi Ascher M. Yager\n* Mrs. Harry Lang\n* Allen Lesser\n* Nathan D. Shapiro\n* Maurice Tishman\n* Mrs. Vivienne T. Wechter\n* Charles Kreindler, International Ladies Garment Workers Union, AFL\n* Louis Nelson, International Ladies Garment Workers Union, AFL<ref name=Unit/>\n\n(Pasternak had a seat on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=Judges/>)  [[Roy Cohn]] joined as a member of the board of directors.<ref name=Krause/>  Anti-communist journalist [[Isaac Don Levine]] was also a co-founder.<ref name=Judges/>\n\nOn May 31, 1948, Schultz testified in support of the [[Mundt-Nixon Bill]].  In July 1948, Sokolsky mentioned formation of an AJLAC office in Los Angeles.  In early 1949, Schultz testified to the Brooklyn Board of Education against the Jewish Peoples Fraternal Order, a member of the Communist-controlled [[International Workers Order]]; a week later, the board followed his recommendation and banned the group from classrooms.  In March 1949, he publicly opposed a Soviet delegation led by [[Dmitri Shostakovich]] from entering the United States.  Schultz also attacked [[Paul Robeson]] during the latter's hearings before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]].<ref name=Krause/>\n\n==Formation==\n[[File:McCarthy Cohn.jpg|thumb|right|[[Roy Cohn]] (here with US Senaotor [[Joseph McCarthy]] during [[Army\u2013McCarthy hearings]] in 1953) was a board member of AJLAC, a core coalition member of the Joint Committee Against Communism: both Cohn and McCarthy later received public recognition from the committee]]\nIn late January 1950, the committee formed in response to a call from [[George N. Craig|George Craig]], head of the American Legion, when 60 national organizations.<ref name=Krause/>\n\nThe founders of the Joint Committee Against Communism were:  \n* Rabbi Benjamin Schultz, executive director, American Jewish League Against Communism\n* Alfred Kohlberg, chairman, American Jewish League Against Communism\n* [[Theodore Kirkpatrick]], managing editor, ''[[Red Channels]]'' and founder, ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)|Counterattack]]''\nKohlberg, a prominent member of the [[China Lobby]] and publisher of ''[[Plain Talk]]'' magazine, bankrolled the committee.<ref name=Names>\n{{cite book\n| first = Victor S.\n| last = Navasky\n| title = Naming Names\n| publisher = Viking Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KHpYAAAAMAAJ\n| page = 121\n| date = 1980\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name= Katagiri>\n{{cite book \n| first = Yasuhiro \n| last = Katagiri \n| title = Black Freedom, White Resistance, and Red Menace: Civil Rights and Anticommunism in the Jim Crow South\n| publisher = Louisiana State University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LCFfDwAAQBAJ\n| pages = \n| date = 6 January 2014\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Joint Committee Against Communism drew together a coalition of several New York State groups and sub-groups including the [[American Legion]], the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]], and [[Catholic War Veterans]], and the Veterans Division of AJLAC.<ref name=Taylor>\n{{cite book \n| first = Clarence \n| last = Taylor \n| authorlink = Clarence Taylor\n| title = Reds at the Blackboard\n| publisher = Columbia University Press\n| url = https://cup.columbia.edu/book/reds-at-the-blackboard/9780231152693\n| pages = 162\u2013163 (composition), 166, 304\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, board members of the committee's core group, AJLAC, included:  Alfred Kohlberg (chair), Benjamin Schultz (executive director), Harry Pasternak (treasurer) as well as [[Bern Dibner]], Lawrence Fertig, Theodore Fine, Benjamin Gitlow, Walter R. Hart, Herman Kashins,  Eugene Lyons, Norman L. Marks, [[Morris Ryskind]], David S. Savitz, Nathan D. Shapiro, George E. Sokolsky, Maurice Tishman, and Ascher  M. Yager.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Michael Collins \n| last = Piper\n| title = The Judas Goats: The Enemy Within\n| publisher = American Free Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uM7zGwAACAAJ\n| date = 2006\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n[[File:Jean-Muir-studio-portrait.jpg|thumb|right|Actor [[Jean Muir (actress)|Jean Muir]] (here, in a [[Warner Bros.]] publicity portrait) came under attack by the committee]]\nIn 1950, the Joint Committee Against Communism called on the New York Board of Education to ban the New York City [[Teachers Union]] (TU), which since the 1930s come under the control of the [[Communist Party USA]].<ref name=Taylor/>  (Former TU vice president Dr. [[Bella Dodd]] would testify before Congress about Communist control of the TU later in the 1950s.)  That same year, the committee helped keep actress [[Jean Muir (actress)|Jean Muir]] banned from radio, soon after her name had appeared in ''Red Channels''.<ref name=Names/>  Also in that year, the committee scared [[Bing Crosby]] away from recording the song \"Old Man Atom\", written by [[Vern Partlow]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' and finally recorded by [[Sam Hinton]].  (The song's lyrics included the lines, \"[[Albert Einstein|Einstein]]'s scared, and when Einstein's scared, I'm scared.\")<ref name=Judges/><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Old Man Atom\n| publisher = Sound Beat\n| url = https://soundbeat.org/episode/old-man-atom/\n| date = 24 October 2019\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  Partlow was a member of [[People's Songs]], a left-wing publisher based in [[New York City]] and founded by folk-singer [[Pete Seeger]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| first = Laura\n| last = Wiener\n| title = Pete Seeger:  The Communist Consumers Love\n| publisher = First Things\n| url = https://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2014/01/peter-seeger-the-communist-consumers-love\n| date = January 2014\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1951, Schultz attacked the reputation of Fleet Admiral [[Chester W. Nimitz]] and US Secretary of Defense General [[George C. Marshall]].  That same year, conservative journalist [[Westbrook Pegler]] wrote a supportive syndicated article called \"Let Me Introduce Rabbi Benjamin Schultz.\"<ref name=Krause/>\n\nIn 1952, the committee honored US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] with a dinner at the [[Astor Hotel]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = McCarthy Holding Plaque For Fighting Communism\n| publisher = Getty Images\n| url = https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/senator-joseph-mccarthy-shows-the-plaque-presented-to-him-news-photo/514704590\n| date = 10 December 1952\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  That same year, the committee named 18 college professors as \"politically objectionable\" and called for legislation against them; the committee declared that \"it is up to the professors to prove their fitness to teach in the face of its accusations.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Conformity Reigns\n| journal = The Crimson\n| publisher = Harvard University\n| url = https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1952/1/17/conformity-reigns-ptwo-conflicting-analyses-of/\n| date = 17 January 1952\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  In a speech in Lansing, Michigan, Schulz denounced both former First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] and [[Americans for Democratic Action]] (ADA), a group she supported and which he called \"an organizational extension of that lady's personality...  more dangerous than Communism.\"<ref name=Judges/>\n\nBy 1953, the committee's original members in AJLAC had become known among leading Jewish \"anti-Reds\" and included:  Eugene Lyons, [[Isaac Don Levine]], [[David Lawrence (publisher)|David Lawrence]], George Sokolsky, [[Benjamin Mandel]], [[Barney Balaban]], Rabbi Ben Schultz, Maurice Tishman, and [[Victor Riesel]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Victor\n| last = Lasky\n| authorlink = Victor Lasky\n| title = The Writers' Forum Holds Professional Bigots Playing Moscow's Game\n| newspaper = Brooklyn Daily Eagle\n| url = https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/53900649/\n| page = 8\n| date = 6 July 1953\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the ... Congress, Volume 99, Part 12\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=A2zBwRqVNcAC&dq\n| page = A4181\n| date = 1953\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, the committee honored [[Roy Cohn]] with a dinner at the [[Astor Hotel]]; US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] was the principal speaker at the dinner.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Cohn and McCarthy Wave to Crowd\n| publisher = Getty Images\n| url = https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/new-york-ny-former-chief-counsel-for-the-senate-news-photo/514876912\n| date = 28 July 1954\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| first = Peter\n| last = Carlson\n| title = Joe McCarthy\u2019s sidekick and Donald Trump\u2019s mentor was not a very nice man\n| publisher = HistoryNet\n| url = https://www.historynet.com/roy-cohn-the-toughest-meanest-most-brilliant-lawyer-in-new-york.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 24 July 2017}}</ref>  Also in 1954, Rabbi Schultz spoke before an American Legion gathering in Boston.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Jewish Community Relations Council, Boston, Massachusetts\n| publisher = American Ancestors\n| url = http://digitalcollections.americanancestors.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15869coll1/id/121059/\n| date = 1954\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1955, the committee honored Myers Lowman for exposing communist influence.<ref name= Katagiri/>  AJLAC honored [[Ruth Shipley]] with an award for \"a lifetime of service to the American people.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Mrs. Shipley Cited by Anti-Red Groups\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1955/05/11/archives/mrs-shipley-cited-by-antired-group.html\n| date = 11 May 1955 \n| accessdate = 22 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn 1950, ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine lumped the Joint Committee Against Communism and its founder Benjamin Schultz with the newsletter ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)|Counterattack]]'' and its founder Theodore Kirkpatrick.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Letters, Oct. 2, 1950\n| work = TIME\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,813396,00.html\n| date = 2 October 1950\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was the committee's 1952 attack on actress Jean Muir that first brought it to public attention.<ref name=Judges/>\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''Soviet Russia and Jews'' (undated pamphlet) (AJLAC)<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| title = A Checklist of Books Dealing with Various Aspects of Communism\n| magazine = American Legion Magazine\n| url = https://archive.legion.org/handle/20.500.12203/3993\n| page = 23\n| date = August 1953\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Mundt-Nixon Bill]]\n* [[Alfred Kohlberg]]\n* ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)]]''\n* ''[[Red Channels]]: The Report of Communist Influence in Radio and Television''\n* ''[[Plain Talk]]''\n* [[Anti-communism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://findingaids.library.columbia.edu/ead/nnc-rb/ldpd_5010936/dsc Group Research Inc. records, 1955-1996]:  box 184 \"Joint Committee Against Communism in New York\"\n* [https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf0b69n3tv/entire_text/ Register of the Alfred Kohlberg papers]: box 98 \"Joint Committee Against Communism in New York\"\n* [https://archive.org/details/AmericanJewishLeagueAgainstCommunismLosAngeles80236/page/n22/mode/2up Archive.org]:  American Jewish League Against Communism \u2013 Los Angeles 80-236\n\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1950]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:1950 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States political action committees]]\n[[Category:Right-wing politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Joint Committee Against Communism\n| pronounce           = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| named_after         = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = \n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = <!-- use {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> January 1950\n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> late 1950s?\n| founder             = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz\n| founding_location   = [[New York City]]\n| merger              = \n| type                = \n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = \n| headquarters        =\n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = \n| services            = \n| methods             = \n| fields              = \n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| language            = \n| sec_gen             = \n| leader_title        = Chairman\n| leader_name         = [[Alfred Kohlberg]]\n| leader_title2       = Executive Director\n| leader_name2        = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz\n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = Theodore Kirkpatrick, [[Roy Cohn]]\n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)]]'', ''[[Red Channels]]'' newsletter, ''[[Plain Talk]]'' magazine\n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\nThe '''Joint Committee Against Communism''', also known as the '''Joint Committee Against Communism in New York''', was an [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]] organization during the 1950s.<ref name=Krause>\n{{cite journal\n| first1 = Allen\n| last1 = Krause\n| title = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz and the American Jewish League Against Communism:  From McCarthy to Mississippi\n| journal = Southern Jewish History\n| publisher = Southern Jewish Historical Society\n| url = https://www.academia.edu/41725935/Allen_Krause_Rabbi_Benjamin_Schultz_and_the_American_Jewish_League_Against_Communism_From_McCarthy_to_Mississippi\n| pages = 167 (quote), 208 (fn25 on founding)\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=SJH>\n{{cite journal\n| first1 = Allen\n| last1 = Krause\n| title = Rabbi Benjamin Schultz and the American Jewish League Against Communism:  From McCarthy to Mississippi\n| journal = Southern Jewish History\n| publisher = Southern Jewish Historical Society\n| url = https://www.jewishsouth.org/index-authors\n| pages = \n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Beim>\n{{cite journal\n| first1 = Aaron\n| last1 = Beim\n| first2 = Gary Alan\n| last2 = Fine\n| title = The Cultural Framework of Prejudice:  Reputational Images and the Postwar Disjuncture of Jews and Communism\n| journal = The Sociological Quarterly\n| publisher = Taylor & Francies\n| url = https://www.jstor.org/stable/40220030?seq=1\n| pages = 373\u2013397\n| date = 1997\n| accessdate = 2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Lyons-Eugene-1940.jpg|thumb|right|[[Eugene Lyons]] (1940) was a co-founder of the committee's core coalition member, American Jewish League Against Communism, Inc. (AJLAC)]]\n[[Benjamin Schultz]] of [[Rochester, New York]], had studied under Rabbi [[Stephen S. Wise]] at the Jewish Institute of Religion in New York City.  He was ordained as a rabbi in 1931 and served a Reform congregation, Temple Emanu-El in [[Yonkers, New York]].  From October 14 to 16, 1947, Schultz published a series of articles in the ''[[New York World-Telegram]]'' on Communism among Protestant and Catholic churches and Jewish synagogues.  He attacked the Reverend Dr. [[Harry F. Ward]] of [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]], [[Abraham Cronbach]] of [[Hebrew Union College]], and Stephen S. Wise by name.<ref name=Krause/>\n\nOn March 15, 1948, Schultz announced in the ''New York Times'' the founding of the American Jewish League Against Communism, Inc. (AJLAC).  AJLAC claimed to side with an \"overwhelming majority of American Jewry\" against Communism.  It praised [[David Dubinsky]], [[Abraham Cahan]], [[Walter Winchell]], and [[David Lawrence (publisher)|David Lawrence]].  Schultz declared, \"Zionism and communism are incompatible.\"<ref name=Judges>\n{{cite book\n| first = Merle\n| last = Miller\n| title = The Judges and the Judged\n| publisher = Doublday\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wM9AAAAAIAAJ\n| page = 153 (AJLAC), 154 (Muir), 155, 156 (Levine), 157 (Roosevelt, ADA), 178 (Old Man Atom)\n| date = 1952\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  Headquartered at 220 West Forty-second Street, AJLAC sought to remove \"all Communist activity in Jewish life, wherever it may be.\"<ref name=Unit>\n{{cite news\n| title = \"Jewish Unit Vows Communist Purge\" \n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/15/archives/jewish-unit-vows-communist-purge-league-forms-here-to-ferret-out.html \n| page = 7\n| date = 15 March 1948\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAJLAC national organizing members included:\n* Benjamin Schultz (executive director)\n* [[Alfred Kohlberg]] (chairman), listed as \"head of the board of directors of the American-China Policy Association, Inc.\"\n* Harry Pasternak, retired realtor (treasurer)\n* [[Benjamin Gitlow]], former general secretary of the [[Communist Party USA]]\n* [[George Sokolsky]], nationally syndicated columnist\n* [[Eugene Lyons]], nationally syndicated columnist\n* [[Isaac Don Levine]], nationally syndicated columnist and editor of ''[[Plain Talk]]''\n* Rabbi David S. Savitz\n* Rabbi Ascher M. Yager\n* Mrs. Harry Lang\n* Allen Lesser\n* Nathan D. Shapiro\n* Maurice Tishman\n* Mrs. Vivienne T. Wechter\n* Charles Kreindler, International Ladies Garment Workers Union, AFL\n* Louis Nelson, International Ladies Garment Workers Union, AFL<ref name=Unit/>\n\n(Pasternak had a seat on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=Judges/>)  [[Roy Cohn]] joined as a member of the board of directors.<ref name=Krause/>  Anti-communist journalist [[Isaac Don Levine]] was also a co-founder.<ref name=Judges/>\n\nOn May 31, 1948, Schultz testified in support of the [[Mundt-Nixon Bill]].  In July 1948, Sokolsky mentioned formation of an AJLAC office in Los Angeles.  In early 1949, Schultz testified to the Brooklyn Board of Education against the Jewish Peoples Fraternal Order, a member of the Communist-controlled [[International Workers Order]]; a week later, the board followed his recommendation and banned the group from classrooms.  In March 1949, he publicly opposed a Soviet delegation led by [[Dmitri Shostakovich]] from entering the United States.  Schultz also attacked [[Paul Robeson]] during the latter's hearings before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]].<ref name=Krause/>\n\n==Formation==\n[[File:McCarthy Cohn.jpg|thumb|right|[[Roy Cohn]] (here with US Senaotor [[Joseph McCarthy]] during [[Army\u2013McCarthy hearings]] in 1953) was a board member of AJLAC, a core coalition member of the Joint Committee Against Communism: both Cohn and McCarthy later received public recognition from the committee]]\nIn late January 1950, the committee formed in response to a call from [[George Craig]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}, head of the American Legion, when 60 national organizations.<ref name=Krause/>\n\nThe founders of the Joint Committee Against Communism were:  \n* Rabbi Benjamin Schultz, executive director, American Jewish League Against Communism\n* Alfred Kohlberg, chairman, American Jewish League Against Communism\n* [[Theodore Kirkpatrick]], managing editor, ''[[Red Channels]]'' and founder, ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)|Counterattack]]''\nKohlberg, a prominent member of the [[China Lobby]] and publisher of ''[[Plain Talk]]'' magazine, bankrolled the committee.<ref name=Names>\n{{cite book\n| first = Victor S.\n| last = Navasky\n| title = Naming Names\n| publisher = Viking Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KHpYAAAAMAAJ\n| page = 121\n| date = 1980\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name= Katagiri>\n{{cite book \n| first = Yasuhiro \n| last = Katagiri \n| title = Black Freedom, White Resistance, and Red Menace: Civil Rights and Anticommunism in the Jim Crow South\n| publisher = Louisiana State University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LCFfDwAAQBAJ\n| pages = \n| date = 6 January 2014\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Joint Committee Against Communism drew together a coalition of several New York State groups and sub-groups including the [[American Legion]], the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]], and [[Catholic War Veterans]], and the Veterans Division of AJLAC.<ref name=Taylor>\n{{cite book \n| first = Clarence \n| last = Taylor \n| authorlink = Clarence Taylor\n| title = Reds at the Blackboard\n| publisher = Columbia University Press\n| url = https://cup.columbia.edu/book/reds-at-the-blackboard/9780231152693\n| pages = 162\u2013163 (composition), 166, 304\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, board members of the committee's core group, AJLAC, included:  Alfred Kohlberg (chair), Benjamin Schultz (executive director), Harry Pasternak (treasurer) as well as [[Bern Dibner]], Lawrence Fertig, Theodore Fine, Benjamin Gitlow, Walter R. Hart, Herman Kashins,  Eugene Lyons, Norman L. Marks, [[Morris Ryskind]], David S. Savitz, Nathan D. Shapiro, George E. Sokolsky, Maurice Tishman, and Ascher  M. Yager.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Michael Collins \n| last = Piper\n| title = The Judas Goats: The Enemy Within\n| publisher = American Free Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uM7zGwAACAAJ\n| date = 2006\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n[[File:Jean-Muir-studio-portrait.jpg|thumb|right|Actor [[Jean Muir (actress)|Jean Muir]] (here, in a [[Warner Bros.]] publicity portrait) came under attack by the committee]]\nIn 1950, the Joint Committee Against Communism called on the New York Board of Education to ban the New York City [[Teachers Union]] (TU), which since the 1930s come under the control of the [[Communist Party USA]].<ref name=Taylor/>  (Former TU vice president Dr. [[Bella Dodd]] would testify before Congress about Communist control of the TU later in the 1950s.)  That same year, the committee helped keep actress [[Jean Muir (actress)|Jean Muir]] banned from radio, soon after her name had appeared in ''Red Channels''.<ref name=Names/>  Also in that year, the committee scared [[Bing Crosby]] away from recording the song \"Old Man Atom\", written by [[Vern Partlow]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' and finally recorded by [[Sam Hinton]].  (The song's lyrics included the lines, \"[[Albert Einstein|Einstein]]'s scared, and when Einstein's scared, I'm scared.\")<ref name=Judges/><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Old Man Atom\n| publisher = Sound Beat\n| url = https://soundbeat.org/episode/old-man-atom/\n| date = 24 October 2019\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  Partlow was a member of [[People's Songs]], a left-wing publisher based in [[New York City]] and founded by folk-singer [[Pete Seeger]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| first = Laura\n| last = Wiener\n| title = Pete Seeger:  The Communist Consumers Love\n| publisher = First Things\n| url = https://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2014/01/peter-seeger-the-communist-consumers-love\n| date = January 2014\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1951, Schultz attacked the reputation of Fleet Admiral [[Chester W. Nimitz]] and US Secretary of Defense General [[George C. Marshall]].  That same year, conservative journalist [[Westbrook Pegler]] wrote a supportive syndicated article called \"Let Me Introduce Rabbi Benjamin Schultz.\"<ref name=Krause/>\n\nIn 1952, the committee honored US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] with a dinner at the [[Astor Hotel]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = McCarthy Holding Plaque For Fighting Communism\n| publisher = Getty Images\n| url = https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/senator-joseph-mccarthy-shows-the-plaque-presented-to-him-news-photo/514704590\n| date = 10 December 1952\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  That same year, the committee named 18 college professors as \"politically objectionable\" and called for legislation against them; the committee declared that \"it is up to the professors to prove their fitness to teach in the face of its accusations.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Conformity Reigns\n| journal = The Crimson\n| publisher = Harvard University\n| url = https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1952/1/17/conformity-reigns-ptwo-conflicting-analyses-of/\n| date = 17 January 1952\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>  In a speech in Lansing, Michigan, Schulz denounced both former First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] and [[Americans for Democratic Action]] (ADA), a group she supported and which he called \"an organizational extension of that lady's personality...  more dangerous than Communism.\"<ref name=Judges/>\n\nBy 1953, the committee's original members in AJLAC had become known among leading Jewish \"anti-Reds\" and included:  Eugene Lyons, [[Isaac Don Levine]], [[David Lawrence (publisher)|David Lawrence]], George Sokolsky, [[Benjamin Mandel]], [[Barney Balaban]], Rabbi Ben Schultz, Maurice Tishman, and [[Victor Riesel]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Victor\n| last = Lasky\n| authorlink = Victor Lasky\n| title = The Writers' Forum Holds Professional Bigots Playing Moscow's Game\n| newspaper = Brooklyn Daily Eagle\n| url = https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/53900649/\n| page = 8\n| date = 6 July 1953\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the ... Congress, Volume 99, Part 12\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=A2zBwRqVNcAC&dq\n| page = A4181\n| date = 1953\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, the committee honored [[Roy Cohn]] with a dinner at the [[Astor Hotel]]; US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] was the principal speaker at the dinner.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Cohn and McCarthy Wave to Crowd\n| publisher = Getty Images\n| url = https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/new-york-ny-former-chief-counsel-for-the-senate-news-photo/514876912\n| date = 28 July 1954\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| first = Peter\n| last = Carlson\n| title = Joe McCarthy\u2019s sidekick and Donald Trump\u2019s mentor was not a very nice man\n| publisher = HistoryNet\n| url = https://www.historynet.com/roy-cohn-the-toughest-meanest-most-brilliant-lawyer-in-new-york.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 24 July 2017}}</ref>  Also in 1954, Rabbi Schultz spoke before an American Legion gathering in Boston.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Jewish Community Relations Council, Boston, Massachusetts\n| publisher = American Ancestors\n| url = http://digitalcollections.americanancestors.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15869coll1/id/121059/\n| date = 1954\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1955, the committee honored Myers Lowman for exposing communist influence.<ref name= Katagiri/>  AJLAC honored [[Ruth Shipley]] with an award for \"a lifetime of service to the American people.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Mrs. Shipley Cited by Anti-Red Groups\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1955/05/11/archives/mrs-shipley-cited-by-antired-group.html\n| date = 11 May 1955 \n| accessdate = 22 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn 1950, ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine lumped the Joint Committee Against Communism and its founder Benjamin Schultz with the newsletter ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)|Counterattack]]'' and its founder Theodore Kirkpatrick.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Letters, Oct. 2, 1950\n| work = TIME\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,813396,00.html\n| date = 2 October 1950\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was the committee's 1952 attack on actress Jean Muir that first brought it to public attention.<ref name=Judges/>\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''Soviet Russia and Jews'' (undated pamphlet) (AJLAC)<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| title = A Checklist of Books Dealing with Various Aspects of Communism\n| magazine = American Legion Magazine\n| url = https://archive.legion.org/handle/20.500.12203/3993\n| page = 23\n| date = August 1953\n| accessdate = 21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Mundt-Nixon Bill]]\n* [[Alfred Kohlberg]]\n* ''[[Counterattack (newsletter)]]''\n* ''[[Red Channels]]: The Report of Communist Influence in Radio and Television''\n* ''[[Plain Talk]]''\n* [[Anti-communism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://findingaids.library.columbia.edu/ead/nnc-rb/ldpd_5010936/dsc Group Research Inc. records, 1955-1996]:  box 184 \"Joint Committee Against Communism in New York\"\n* [https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf0b69n3tv/entire_text/ Register of the Alfred Kohlberg papers]: box 98 \"Joint Committee Against Communism in New York\"\n* [https://archive.org/details/AmericanJewishLeagueAgainstCommunismLosAngeles80236/page/n22/mode/2up Archive.org]:  American Jewish League Against Communism \u2013 Los Angeles 80-236\n\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1950]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:1950 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States political action committees]]\n[[Category:Right-wing politics]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGeorge Craig(link changed toGeorge N. Craig) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Committee_Against_Communism"}
{"title_page": "Overseas Chinese", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2015}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Overseas Chinese \n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6d77\u5916\u534e\u4eba}}/{{lang|zh-Hant|\u6d77\u5916\u83ef\u4eba}}<br />{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6d77\u5916\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba}}/{{lang|zh-Hant|\u6d77\u5916\u4e2d\u570b\u4eba}}}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| population = '''{{Circa|50 million}}'''<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |author=\u5f35\u660e\u611b |url = http://www.china.org.cn/china/NPC_CPPCC_2012/2012-03/11/content_24865428.htm |title=Reforms urged to attract overseas Chinese |website = China.org.cn |date=2012-03-11 |accessdate=2012-05-28 }}</ref><ref \nname=\"chinadaily.com.cn\">{{cite web |url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2012-04/09/content_15007664.htm |title = Hu meets overseas Chinese organizations leaders&#124;Politics |website = chinadaily.com.cn |date=2012-04-09 |accessdate=2012-05-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Huiyao Wang 2\">{{cite web |url = http://www.asiapacific.ca/sites/default/files/filefield/researchreportv7.pdf |title = China's Competition for Global Talents: Strategy, Policy and Recommendations |publisher=Asia Pacific |date = 24 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012 |first = Huiyao |last = Wang |page = 2 }}</ref><ref>http://www.culturaldiplomacy.org/academy/index.php?chinese-diaspora. Chinese Diaspora Across the World</ref><br />{{small|(2018 estimate)}}\n| region1 = {{flag|Thailand}}\n| pop1 = [[Thai Chinese|9,349,900]]\n| ref1 = <ref name=\"West794\">{{citation |first = Barbara A. |last = West |title = Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Asia and Oceania |publisher=Facts on File |year=2009 |page=794 |isbn = 978-1438119137 }}</ref>\n| region2 = {{flag|Malaysia}}\n| pop2 = [[Malaysian Chinese|6,642,000]]\n| ref2 = <ref name=\"2015 population\">{{cite web |url = http://pmr.penerangan.gov.my/index.php/info-terkini/19463-unjuran-populasi-penduduk-2015.html |title=Population by States and Ethnic Group |publisher=Department of Information, Ministry of Communications and Multimedia, Malaysia |year=2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160212125740/http://pmr.penerangan.gov.my/index.php/info-terkini/19463-unjuran-populasi-penduduk-2015.html |archivedate=12 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| region3 = {{flag|United States}}\n| pop3 = [[Chinese Americans|5,025,817]]\n| ref3 = <ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.census.gov |title = ASIAN ALONE OR IN ANY COMBINATION BY SELECTED GROUPS |publisher = U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate = 2 February 2020 }}</ref>\n| region4 = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n| pop4 = [[Chinese Indonesians|2,832,510]]\n| ref4 = <ref name=\"daftar sensus 2010\">{{cite book |publisher=Badan Pusat Statistik \n|title=Kewarganegaraan, Suku Bangsa, Agama dan Bahasa Sehari-hari Penduduk Indonesia Hasil Sensus Penduduk 2010 |year=2011|isbn=9789790644175 |url = http://sp2010.bps.go.id/files/ebook/kewarganegaraan%20penduduk%20indonesia/index.html|access-date=6 December 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170710134114/http://sp2010.bps.go.id/files/ebook/kewarganegaraan%20penduduk%20indonesia/index.html |archive-date=10 July 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| region5 = {{flag|Singapore}}\n| pop5 = [[Chinese Singaporeans|2,571,000]]\n| ref5 = <ref name=\"highlights2015\">{{cite web |url = http://www.nptd.gov.sg/Portals/0/Homepage/Highlights/population-in-brief-2015.pdf |title=Population in Brief 2015 |work=Singapore Government|date=September 2015|accessdate=14 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216110141/http://www.nptd.gov.sg/Portals/0/Homepage/Highlights/population-in-brief-2015.pdf|archivedate=16 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| region6 = {{flag|Canada}}\n| pop6 = [[Chinese Canadians|1,769,195]]\n| ref6 = <ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&SearchText=Canada&SearchType